import { Manifest } from './types';
export const manifest: Manifest = {"meta":{"source":"Article_kepler-flywheel-decade.docx","governing_thought":"The market looks at Kepler and sees a conglomerate: six physical-world businesses — mobility, energy, logistics, payments, devices, and the data platform beneath them — stapled together under one brand, each trailing a focused specialist in its own vertical, the whole priced at a ~35% conglomerate discount to the sum of its parts.","title":"Kepler","kicker":"A ten-year strategy for the operating system of the physical world"},"nodes":{"GT":{"id":"GT","level":1,"parent":null,"path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade"],"title":"Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","body":"<p>The market looks at Kepler and sees a conglomerate: six physical-world businesses — mobility, energy, logistics, payments, devices, and the data platform beneath them — stapled together under one brand, each trailing a focused specialist in its own vertical, the whole priced at a ~35% conglomerate discount to the sum of its parts. On that reading, the obvious move is to break Kepler up: spin the six out, let each compete on its own, unlock the discount.</p><p>That reading is wrong, and this document exists to prove it wrong at the mechanism level. Kepler is not six businesses. It is one flywheel. Every physical-world interaction it touches — a ride requested, a battery charged, a parcel delivered, a payment cleared, a device pinged — produces data and network effects that no single-vertical competitor can assemble, because no single-vertical competitor touches the physical world across all six surfaces at once. That shared data-and-network moat is the actual asset. The six businesses are the organs that feed it, and the moat, in turn, lowers cost and raises trust back across all six. Break Kepler up and you don't unlock value; you destroy the only thing about it that was ever defensible.</p><p>The governing thought: Kepler is one flywheel, not six businesses, and the entire strategy is sequencing the six domains so each compounds the moat — not running them as a conglomerate. Sequence them right and the moat becomes uncatchable; run them as silos and it never forms. The decade is won or lost on sequencing, not on any single business.</p><p>The rest of this document is that claim, proven domain by domain, drilled to the mechanism level where the compounding is real or it is nothing — and then reassembled into the flywheel that is the whole point.</p>","component":{"family":"network","data":{"hub":{"label":"Kep","sub":"the moat"},"spokes":[{"label":"D1","sub":"Autonomous Mobility"},{"label":"D2","sub":"Energy & Charging"},{"label":"D3","sub":"Logistics Marketplace"},{"label":"D4","sub":"Payments & Fintech"},{"label":"D5","sub":"Devices & Hardware"},{"label":"D6","sub":"Data & AI Platform"}],"caption":"every feed is also a return — no domain a leaf"},"evidence_class":"illustrate"},"children":[]},"D1":{"id":"D1","level":2,"parent":"GT","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility"],"title":"Domain 1 — Autonomous Mobility: the density engine that feeds everything else","body":"<p>Mobility is where Kepler touches the physical world most often, and frequency is the point. In the moat identity M = D × B × L × T, this domain owns Interaction density (D) outright — the sheer count of geolocated, time-stamped, behaviourally-rich events per square kilometre per hour — and it is the only domain that manufactures D at industrial scale. Every ride is a probe: it measures a street, a curb, a queue, a payment, a rider's tolerance for a three-minute wait. At 41% of the $9.4bn top line, mobility is also the cash and data furnace that the other five draw on. The argument of this section is narrow and load-bearing: D is not a vanity metric; it is the raw feedstock that lowers cost and raises trust everywhere else, and mobility is the only domain that can move it by an order of magnitude.</p><p>The cross-feeds are the whole reason D matters. Mobility's dwell-and-idle heatmaps tell Energy (D2) where to site chargers before demand exists (trace S-118). Its origin-destination tensor is the demand prior that Logistics (D3) routes couriers against (S-112). Its device-fingerprint-plus-trajectory stream is the strongest single fraud signal Payments (D4) consumes (S-116). Its vehicle sensors are the highest-volume input to Devices (D5) telemetry and to every model in Data/AI (D6) (S-121). Read alone, mobility is a good-not-great robotaxi business trailing a focused specialist. Read as the D-engine of a flywheel, it is the domain that makes the other five cheaper to run than any standalone competitor can achieve. This section develops that claim through four drivers, each mechanism chaining into the next.</p>","finding":"Mobility is the only domain that manufactures Interaction…","finding_full":"<p>What's true. On its own numbers, Kepler mobility is a strong-but-not-singular robotaxi operation. It runs a dense, safe, well-instrumented fleet; utilization in saturated zones clears 70%; miles-per-intervention improved 11.6× in a year; the rider app is good. A focused robotaxi specialist could match most of this line by line, and on a sum-of-the-parts read the market would be right to price mobility as one competent vertical inside a discounted conglomerate. The sensor stack still loses money per ride until solid-state lidar lands. None of this, standing alone, is uncatchable.</p><p>What counts.</p>","children":["D1.d1","D1.d2","D1.d3","D1.d4"]},"D1.d1":{"id":"D1.d1","level":3,"parent":"D1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The fleet and the density engine"],"title":"Driver 1 — The fleet and the density engine","body":"<p>Density is not bought; it is compounded <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-008\">S-008</button>. The fleet is the physical instrument that converts capital into interactions, and the discipline is to concentrate that instrument until the data it produces crosses a usefulness threshold — then hold it there while demand catches up <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-008\">S-008</button>. This driver owns <strong>D</strong>, the data term of the moat identity M = D × B × L × T: inside an already-dense zone every additional interaction sharpens the routing and pricing models rather than merely adding revenue, which is why concentration, not coverage, is the governing rule and why the two mechanisms below both bend toward holding a saturated core rather than spreading a thin blanket <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-009\">S-009</button>.</p>","children":["D1.d1.m1","D1.d1.m2"]},"D1.d1.m1":{"id":"D1.d1.m1","level":4,"parent":"D1.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The fleet and the density engine","The density-first deployment rule"],"title":"The density-first deployment rule","body":"<p>Kepler does not spread vehicles to maximise city coverage; it floods zones until interaction density per km² per hour crosses the threshold where the routing and pricing models stop guessing <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-009\">S-009</button>. <strong>Below roughly 40 interactions/km²/hr the models are extrapolating; above it they are interpolating</strong>, and every downstream prediction — ETA, surge, charger dwell — sharpens. The mechanism moves D directly: rather than 300 vehicles thin across a metro, Kepler runs 1,100 inside three contiguous zones <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-009\">S-009</button>. The trade-off is brutal and deliberate — visible under-service at the metro edge, and a press narrative of \"Kepler abandoned the suburbs,\" accepted because a dense core produces data that a thin blanket never will <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-101\">S-101</button>.</p><p>The faceted map renders the rule as a metro canvas of named zones, each labelled with active vehicles and utilization (revenue-minutes ÷ available-minutes). Its decisive contrast is <strong>Marina Core at 71% against Noord Fringe at 39%</strong>: the same vehicle earns and learns nearly twice as much inside the saturated zone <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-102\">S-102</button>. Noord Fringe is the edge-case the rule tolerates — a starving polygon kept deliberately thin so capital flows to Marina Core <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-102\">S-102</button>. Saturated zones are outlined solid; sub-threshold zones are hatched, a standing to-do list of where density has not yet been bought. The Reforma Corridor sits between the two states, ramping toward the 40-interaction floor: it is where the rule is being executed rather than defended, and its trajectory over the next three quarters is the leading indicator of whether the density-first thesis generalises beyond Singapore and Amsterdam's founding geometry <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-009\">S-009</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["Zone (city)","Active AVs","Utilization","Interactions/km²/hr","Status"],"rows":[["Marina Core (Singapore)","420","71%","63","Saturated — data-complete"],["Jurong Spine (Singapore)","260","58%","44","At threshold"],["Amstel Ring (Amsterdam)","310","66%","51","Saturated — data-complete"],["Noord Fringe (Amsterdam)","140","39%","22","Sub-threshold — starving"],["Jumeirah Belt (Dubai)","380","68%","55","Saturated — data-complete"],["Reforma Corridor (Mexico City)","290","52%","34","Below threshold — ramping"]],"negCols":[]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D1.d1.m2":{"id":"D1.d1.m2","level":4,"parent":"D1.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The fleet and the density engine","Holding the floor with a utilization time-series"],"title":"Holding the floor with a utilization time-series","body":"<p>Concentration only compounds if utilization stays high enough that the fleet is interacting rather than idling — an idle AV produces no D and burns the depreciation that Driver 4 quantifies <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-010\">S-010</button>. Kepler manages the fleet against a <strong>utilization floor</strong>, dispatching repositioning moves and dynamic pricing — fed by D4's cash-free rails — whenever a zone threatens to slip beneath it. The mechanism moves D by protecting the denominator of interactions-per-vehicle; the number it moves is weekday utilization, <strong>held above the 60% floor in saturated zones</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-010\">S-010</button>.</p><p>The utilization time-series for Marina Core plots a 24-hour curve, midnight to midnight, against a dashed 60% floor line. Two peaks — 07:30 and 18:15 — clear 80%, while the 14:00 midday trough kisses the floor and triggers repositioning and a fare cut <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-103\">S-103</button>. The edge-case is the trough that breaks the floor: a rain-driven demand collapse on a Tuesday dropped Reforma Corridor to 41% for two hours, the signal that a zone is over-vehicled and capital should rotate out <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-104\">S-104</button>. The chain to Driver 2 is direct — a fleet held at the density floor generates enough incident-free exposure that safety becomes statistically legible, which is the only way to earn the trust the next driver depends on <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-010\">S-010</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Holding the floor with a utilization time-seri","lines":"Util %  Marina Core — weekday utilization vs <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">60</span>% floor <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">90</span> |                    ╭─╮              ╭──╮ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">80</span> |          ╭─╮      ╱   ╲           ╱     ╲ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">70</span> |    ╭────╯   ╲────╯     ╲────╮   ╱        ╲ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">60</span> |╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╲─╱╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╌╲╌╌  ← floor <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">50</span> |  ╱                          ╰╯             ╲ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">40</span> |─╯                                           ╲    +--------------------------------------------------     <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">00</span>   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">03</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">06</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">09</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">12</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">15</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">18</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">21</span>   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">24</span>          AM peak↑          midday dip↓   PM peak↑"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D1.d2":{"id":"D1.d2","level":3,"parent":"D1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","Safety and the trust it earns"],"title":"Driver 2 — Safety and the trust it earns","body":"<p>Density without safety is a liability that regulators close overnight. This driver owns mobility's single contribution to <strong>Trust (T)</strong> — the one moat term besides Density (D) that mobility meaningfully moves — and its logic is narrow but load-bearing: accumulated safe miles are not an asset until they become a <strong>disclosed, auditable record</strong> that regulators and riders both price in <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-011\">S-011</button>. Miles that stay inside Kepler's own warehouse move nothing; miles turned into an inspectable safety record before the next zone permit are what actually lift T. The two mechanisms below are the currency and the ledger — the metric that proves the fleet is getting safer, and the timeline that lets an outside party verify it.</p>","children":["D1.d2.m1","D1.d2.m2"]},"D1.d2.m1":{"id":"D1.d2.m1","level":4,"parent":"D1.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","Safety and the trust it earns","Miles-per-intervention as the trust currency"],"title":"Miles-per-intervention as the trust currency","body":"<p>The operating metric is <strong>miles between safety-critical disengagements</strong> — the distance the fleet covers before a remote operator or safety driver has to take control to avoid harm <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-012\">S-012</button>. Density compounds this metric in a way a single-vertical rival cannot copy: saturated zones run so many miles over the same road geometry that the model sees each rare edge-case — an occluded pedestrian stepping from behind a bus, a cyclist jaywalking against the light — hundreds of times rather than once, so the long tail is learned rather than survived. The mechanism moves T by pushing miles-per-intervention up an order of magnitude, and it is fed by D6's perception models, which are themselves trained on the density D1 produces <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-105\">S-105</button> — the cross-feed that makes the gain circular rather than one-off.</p><p>The evidence is superlinear, and the superlinearity is the whole claim: miles-per-intervention rose <strong>11.6× across four quarters while fleet miles merely tripled</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-106\">S-106</button>. If safety scaled linearly with exposure the two curves would track each other; instead the ratio pulls away, and that widening gap is the density dividend — the same edge-case seen enough times to be modelled instead of merely endured. The trade-off is real and is managed, not ignored: chasing the metric too hard breeds over-cautious \"freezing\" behaviour that tanks the rider experience of Driver 3, so the safety and experience teams are held to one shared objective function, not two <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-012\">S-012</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["Quarter","Miles/critical intervention","Fleet miles (m)","Critical incidents","Zone"],"rows":[["Q1","18,400","22","3","Marina Core"],["Q2","41,200","31","2","Marina Core"],["Q3","96,500","44","1","Marina Core"],["Q4","214,000","58","1","Marina Core"]],"negCols":[]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D1.d2.m2":{"id":"D1.d2.m2","level":4,"parent":"D1.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","Safety and the trust it earns","The incident timeline as an auditable record"],"title":"The incident timeline as an auditable record","body":"<p>Trust is not the average day; it is <strong>how the worst days are handled and disclosed</strong>. Kepler maintains a public safety-incident timeline — every safety-critical event logged, root-caused, and tied to the exact model or hardware change that closed it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-013\">S-013</button>. The mechanism moves T by converting opaque risk into an audit trail a regulator can inspect before granting the next zone permit <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-107\">S-107</button>: disclosure itself becomes the currency that buys licence-to-operate. The trade-off is radical transparency — publishing incidents competitors keep quiet, a genuine short-term reputational cost paid deliberately in exchange for long-term standing with the bodies that hand out permits.</p><p>The Q4 event is the instructive edge-case. Heavy rain attenuated lidar; rather than proceeding blind, the vehicle correctly executed a <strong>minimum-risk pullover</strong>, and the fix — radar-weighted sensor fusion — came straight from Devices (D5) hardware co-design <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-109\">S-109</button>. That is the flywheel made visible inside a single incident: a hardware cross-feed closing a mobility safety gap, then logged in the open where a regulator can trace cause to remedy. The chain to Driver 3 follows directly — a fleet that is both dense and demonstrably safe can finally be sold as an experience, because trust is the precondition a rider needs before any of the app's promises mean anything <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-013\">S-013</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The incident timeline as an auditable record","lines":"SAFETY-INCIDENT TIMELINE — Marina Core + Amstel Ring──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────Q1  ●── Occluded pedestrian, near-miss (no contact)        Root cause: late detection behind parked van        Fix: perception model v4.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1</span>, occlusion prior      [S-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">108</span>]Q2  ●── Low-speed contact w/ cyclist, no injury        Root cause: cyclist against-light, unmodeled path        Fix: intent model + geofenced slow-zoneQ3  ○── Hard brake cluster (comfort, not safety)        Root cause: over-cautious freeze at tram crossing        Fix: tuned caution threshold (see Driver <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span> tension)Q4  ●── Sensor-occlusion (heavy rain), safe pullover        Root cause: lidar attenuation; SAFE degradation        Fix: radar-weighted fusion <span class=\"k\">in</span> rain (Devices D5)   [S-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">109</span>]──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────● safety-critical   ○ comfort-only"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D1.d3":{"id":"D1.d3","level":3,"parent":"D1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The rider experience"],"title":"Driver 3 — The rider experience","body":"<p>Demand density (D) and trust (T) are supply-side terms; they convert to revenue only through a rider who chooses Kepler again. This driver is where <strong>interaction density becomes interaction loyalty</strong> — where the density flywheel either self-reinforces (more riders raise D, which sharpens predictions, which improves the experience, which draws more riders) or stalls out <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-014\">S-014</button>. Mobility's job here is narrow and measurable: lift D by raising ride frequency per rider, and the lever is a rider app that turns model precision into felt reliability <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-014\">S-014</button>.</p>","children":["D1.d3.m1","D1.d3.m2"]},"D1.d3.m1":{"id":"D1.d3.m1","level":4,"parent":"D1.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The rider experience","Precision ETAs as the retention engine"],"title":"Precision ETAs as the retention engine","body":"<p>The single experience variable that most moves rebooking is not speed but <strong>ETA accuracy</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-015\">S-015</button>. A rider forgives a four-minute wait promised as four minutes; they abandon a three-minute wait promised as one — the felt injury is the broken promise, not the delay. Density feeds this directly: saturated zones let the ETA model interpolate from dense recent history rather than extrapolate into thin data, which cuts mean absolute ETA error <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-015\">S-015</button>. That is how the mechanism moves D — by lifting rides-per-active-rider, since frequency is itself density — and it is fed by D6's demand models and the origin-destination tensor mobility itself generates <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-110\">S-110</button>.</p><p>The trade-off is priced, not wished away: guaranteeing tight ETAs sometimes means pre-positioning idle vehicles, which nicks the utilization floor of Driver 1 — a managed tension <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-015\">S-015</button>.</p><p>The rider app makes the copy do three jobs at once:</p><ul><li>\"1,204,000 rides in this zone\" sells density as safety-through-familiarity, cashing Driver 2's trust into legible form.</li><li>\"Kepler Pay · balance auto-charged\" closes the Payments (D4) loop that lets the ride run cash-free <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-111\">S-111</button>.</li><li>\"verified safe\" cashes the Driver 2 safety record at the exact point of decision.</li></ul><p>The edge case is the honest one: when the pod is not pre-positioned and the true ETA is nine minutes, the app says nine — because one broken promise costs more D than one lost ride <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-015\">S-015</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Precision ETAs as the retention engine","lines":"┌───────────────────────────────────────────┐│  KEPLER · now                               ││  Your Kepler is <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">2</span> min away 🚗               ││  Silver pod K-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">4471</span> · Marina Blvd pickup.    ││  We moved it closer — tap to track live.    │└───────────────────────────────────────────┘"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D1.d3.m2":{"id":"D1.d3.m2","level":4,"parent":"D1.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The rider experience","The origin-destination tensor as the shared demand prior"],"title":"The origin-destination tensor as the shared demand prior","body":"<p>Every completed ride writes one cell into an <strong>origin-destination-by-time tensor</strong> — the densest demand map anyone in these cities holds <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-016\">S-016</button>. The mechanism moves D by making the next rider's experience better: the tensor is the prior every ETA and surge decision reads from, so each ride sharpens the model that serves the ride after it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-016\">S-016</button>.</p><p>Its cross-feeds are the flywheel's spine. The same tensor is the demand prior Logistics (D3) routes its couriers against, and the dwell-pattern input Energy (D2) sites its chargers from <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-112\">S-112</button> — one shared warehouse feeding three domains rather than three domains hoarding three warehouses.</p><p>The trade-off is privacy exposure: the tensor is re-identification-sensitive, so it is aggregated and made differentially private before it crosses the mobility boundary — a deliberate loss of resolution accepted to protect trust <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-016\">S-016</button>. The chain forward to Driver 4: an experience this reliable is only defensible if the machine underneath earns money per ride, which is where unit economics decide whether density is an asset or a subsidy <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-016\">S-016</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D1.d4":{"id":"D1.d4","level":3,"parent":"D1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The vehicle and unit economics"],"title":"Driver 4 — The vehicle and unit economics","body":"<p>Density that loses money is a countdown, not a moat. This driver asks a single question — is each incremental interaction accretive? — and it answers with the vehicle itself. The sensor stack that makes autonomy possible is also the cost line that decides the flywheel's terminal contribution, so <strong>mobility moves D only insofar as the per-ride economics let Kepler hold the density rather than retreat from it</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-017\">S-017</button>. Every mechanism below is that question resolved into hardware and into the number the flywheel is chartered to move.</p>","children":["D1.d4.m1","D1.d4.m2"]},"D1.d4.m1":{"id":"D1.d4.m1","level":4,"parent":"D1.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The vehicle and unit economics","The teardown — sensor cost as the swing variable"],"title":"The teardown — sensor cost as the swing variable","body":"<p>The AV is a rolling sensor platform, and its bill of materials is the largest single lever on contribution per interaction — the swing variable that decides whether density is a moat or a countdown <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-018\">S-018</button>. The teardown is not a parts list; it is the cost thesis exploded outward from the chassis, and it maps one-to-one to the safety timeline. The Q4 rain incident's fix — radar-weighted fusion — is precisely why the 4D imaging radar count is five, not three <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-113\">S-113</button>. Reliability, in other words, is priced into the BOM.</p><p>Every one of these sensors is co-designed with Devices (D5), and their raw streams are the proprietary telemetry that widens Data breadth (B) for D6's models. Mobility manufactures D, but the vehicle is the exact point where it hands B to the platform — the sensor is simultaneously a cost line and a data faucet <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-114\">S-114</button>.</p><p>The BOM makes the swing visible in one view. <strong>Lidar is 61% of the sensor bill and the entire cost thesis</strong>: the solid-state roadmap that roughly halves the stack to ~$6,900 is what flips per-ride contribution positive at current density <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-115\">S-115</button>. The trade-off is timing — deploy density now on expensive lidar and eat negative contribution, or wait for cheap lidar and cede the density lead.</p><p>Kepler deploys now, because D compounds and cost is a schedule. A density lead surrendered to save eighteen months of lidar depreciation is a lead a rival, having filled the OD tensor first, may never return. Cost curves bend on a roadmap that engineering controls; density leads, once lost, must be re-bought against an incumbent's better models — an asymmetry that makes the expensive-lidar years a defensible investment rather than a subsidy to be apologised for <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-115\">S-115</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The teardown — sensor cost as the swing variab","lines":"        KEPLER POD — EXPLODED SENSOR STACK                    ┌─────────┐        roof ▸      │ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">2</span>× spinning LIDAR (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">128</span>-beam) │                    └─────────┘     A-pillar ▸  ◐ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">6</span>× surround CAMERA (8MP)      grille  ▸  ▭ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">5</span>× imaging RADAR (4D)     bumper   ▸  ▬ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">12</span>× ultrasonic PROXIMITY      cabin   ▸  ▣ INERTIAL nav unit (IMU/GNSS)      trunk   ▸  ▦ COMPUTE module (autonomy SoC)      wheels  ▸  ⊙ wheel-odometry ENCODERS"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D1.d4.m2":{"id":"D1.d4.m2","level":4,"parent":"D1.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Autonomous Mobility","The vehicle and unit economics","Contribution per interaction — the flywheel's scoreboard"],"title":"Contribution per interaction — the flywheel's scoreboard","body":"<p>The number that ties this domain to the bible's central promise is blended contribution per interaction, which the flywheel is chartered to lift from −0.31 over ten years <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-019\">S-019</button>. Mobility drives its share of that swing through two chained effects. First, density raises utilization (Driver 1), which amortises the vehicle across more paid minutes. Second, the sensor stream widens B (this driver), which sharpens the fraud, routing, and siting models that lower cost across D2, D3, and D4.</p><p>The distinction that matters: the mechanism moves D's value, not its count — the same interaction is worth more once four other domains monetise it. The cross-feed made concrete: <strong>mobility's trajectory-plus-device-fingerprint stream is the strongest single input to Payments (D4) fraud scoring</strong>, and each fraud dollar D4 saves is booked partly against the ride that generated the signal <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-116\">S-116</button>. A ride, priced once, is paid for many times across the flywheel.</p><p>The edge case sharpens the logic. The loss-leader ride — a deliberately under-priced trip in a ramping zone, the Reforma Corridor — carries negative contribution on its own line, but its data closes a coverage gap in the OD tensor. It is an investment in D justified only by the flywheel, never by the ride's own P&amp;L <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-117\">S-117</button>. Judged as a standalone fare it is a mistake; judged as a moat input it is the cheapest breadth Kepler can buy.</p>","children":[]},"D2":{"id":"D2","level":2,"parent":"GT","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging"],"title":"Domain 2 — Energy & Charging: the cost floor and the reliability that earns trust","body":"<p>Energy is the domain that almost nobody underwrites correctly, because on a standalone P&amp;L it looks like the worst business we own: capital-heavy, thin-margined, exposed to a commodity we do not control. Read against the moat identity, though, it is the domain that quietly sets the floor under everything else. Of the four moat terms — M = D × B × L × T — Energy &amp; Charging moves exactly two, and it moves them in a way no other domain can. It compresses the marginal cost of every electron-consuming interaction in the flywheel, and it manufactures Trust (T) the only way trust in physical infrastructure is ever actually manufactured: by being reliable ten thousand times in a row where a competitor is reliable nine thousand nine hundred. It does not touch interaction density (D — that is D1's job), it feeds but does not own data breadth (B — that is D5/D6), and it is agnostic to network liquidity (L — that is D3). Its two levers are cost and T, and the entire investment case for the domain is that these two levers are not local. A charge is not the product. The product is a lower cost floor and a higher trust ceiling that the other five domains draw on for free.</p><p>The cross-feeds are the reason the domain exists inside Kepler rather than as a spun-out charge-point operator trading at a utility multiple. Three couplings carry most of the weight. First, Energy lowers the marginal cost of Mobility (D1) and Logistics (D3) — the same electrons that move an autonomous vehicle move a courier's e-scooter, and owning generation-to-socket economics means we buy those electrons once, at wholesale-plus, instead of twice at retail. Second, siting is fed by Mobility's location data (D1 → D2) — we do not guess where to build chargers; the densest ride and dwell-time data in 42 cities tells us where demand will be eighteen months before a standalone operator can see it. Third, and most strategically, reliability feeds T, and T is the term Payments (D4) is built on — a customer who trusts that the charger works is a customer who trusts the app that dispatched them to it, and eventually the wallet inside that app. Trust is not partitioned by domain in the user's head. We earn it at the socket and spend it at the checkout. This section develops four drivers, each mechanism chaining into the next, and shows where the cost floor and the trust ceiling actually come from.</p>","finding":"Energy moves two moat terms — cost and T — and moves them…","finding_full":"<p>What's true. Energy &amp; Charging is, on its own books, the least attractive standalone business in the portfolio: capital-intensive, exposed to a commodity it cannot control, and margin-thin even in its good branches (probability-weighted +$0.036/kWh is a utility-grade number, not a software one). A focused charge-point specialist, unburdened by the rest of Kepler, would likely operate a leaner balance sheet and trade at a cleaner multiple. All of that is true, and it is why the sum-of-the-parts view marks this domain down.</p><p>What counts. None of that is the point of owning it. What counts is tha</p>","children":["D2.d1","D2.d2","D2.d3","D2.d4"]},"D2.d1":{"id":"D2.d1","level":3,"parent":"D2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","The charging network as an asset"],"title":"Driver 1 — The charging network as an asset","body":"<p>The first question in Energy &amp; Charging is not how many chargers Kepler owns but what the estate actually is: <strong>6,180 charging sites across the 42 cities</strong>, carried on the books as either a cost sink or a compounding asset <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-022\">S-022</button>. That is not an accounting choice — it turns entirely on where the sites sit, and the placement is precisely where the first cross-domain coupling into the flywheel does its work. The two mechanisms below are that coupling, drilled: siting fed by Mobility's data, then the power economics that a well-sited estate unlocks.</p>","children":["D2.d1.m1","D2.d1.m2"]},"D2.d1.m1":{"id":"D2.d1.m1","level":4,"parent":"D2.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","The charging network as an asset","Siting fed by Mobility's location data (D1 → D2)"],"title":"Mechanism 1.1 — Siting fed by Mobility's location data (D1 → D2)","body":"<p>A standalone charge-point operator has one way to decide where capacity goes: it sites against traffic counts and grid-connection availability. That signal is <strong>public, laggy, and available to every competitor at the same moment</strong> — it tells you where demand looked busy last year, not where it will be. Kepler sites against a signal no competitor holds: D1's proprietary dwell-and-dispatch map — where autonomous vehicles actually idle between fares, where riders actually originate, and where the fleet's state-of-charge actually crosses the reorder threshold <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-023\">S-023</button>. This is the flywheel's first turn inside the energy domain. Because D1 generates the densest location-and-behaviour data in the network, Kepler can place a fast-charger on the corner where the fleet will need it in 2027, not the corner that looked busy in 2024 <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-201\">S-201</button>.</p><p>The payoff is measured, not asserted. In the <strong>eleven cities where siting has been driven by D1 telemetry rather than public traffic data, first-year utilization ran 31% higher</strong> than in the legacy-sited estate — the single largest driver of site-level payback in the portfolio <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-201\">S-201</button>. The mechanism matters because utilization is the numerator of every economic in this domain; a mis-sited charger is not a small loss, it is a stranded asset earning grid-connection charges for a decade with nothing on the other side of the ledger.</p><p>The estate itself, rendered as sites × power class × utilization by city, shows why the feed is never generic. In <strong>Jakarta and Ho Chi Minh City the load is dominated by D3's courier fleet on AC chargers</strong>; in <strong>Dubai it is D1's autonomous fleet on DC-fast</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-201\">S-201</button>. The same physical socket serves different domains in different cities — and that is exactly the point. A socket utilised <strong>63% at peak across the network is a socket that two internal customers are paying to keep warm</strong>, a dual-demand profile no single-purpose operator can replicate <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-202\">S-202</button>. Siting quality then chains directly into the next mechanism, because a well-sited, dual-fed estate is what makes ownership of the power economics worth having.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["City","Sites","DC-fast (≥150kW)","AC (≤22kW)","Peak util.","Off-peak util.","Primary demand feed"],"rows":[["Singapore","412","188","224","74%","29%","D1 fleet + D3 couriers"],["Amsterdam","356","141","215","68%","24%","D1 fleet + retail"],["Jakarta","388","96","292","71%","33%","D3 couriers (dominant)"],["Ho Chi Minh City","301","74","227","66%","31%","D3 couriers"],["Dubai","214","132","82","59%","19%","D1 fleet (dominant)"],["Warsaw","176","61","115","52%","21%","Retail + D1"],["Network (42 cities)","6,180","2,214","3,966","63%","26%","mixed"]],"negCols":[0]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D2.d1.m2":{"id":"D2.d1.m2","level":4,"parent":"D2.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","The charging network as an asset","Vertical integration of the power economics"],"title":"Mechanism 1.2 — Vertical integration of the power economics","body":"<p>A well-sited, dual-fed estate is worth owning up the stack. Because Kepler can forecast aggregate load from the same fleet data behind Mechanism 1.1, it can contract power as an <strong>industrial buyer</strong> — long-dated PPAs, wholesale-market participation, on-site storage — rather than paying retail tariffs at each individual socket <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-024\">S-024</button>. The result is a hard number: <strong>blended landed cost of energy across the network is $0.081/kWh against a retail benchmark of $0.163/kWh in the same metros — a 50.3% wholesale-plus discount</strong> that is the raw material of the cost floor <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-203\">S-203</button>.</p><p>This is the mechanism that converts \"we own chargers\" into \"we own the marginal cost of movement.\" It is the hinge for the entire domain, because that <strong>$0.082/kWh gap is what gets handed down to D1 and D3</strong> — the mobility and logistics fleets that draw on the estate — turning an energy-domain cost advantage into a network-wide one <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-024\">S-024</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D2.d2":{"id":"D2.d2","level":3,"parent":"D2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","Load, demand & dispatch"],"title":"Driver 2 — Load, demand & dispatch","body":"<p>Owning cheap electrons is necessary but not sufficient. The first driver secured a low <strong>average</strong> cost of power; it does nothing for the cost that actually shows up in the unit economics — the <strong>marginal</strong> cost at the instant a vehicle plugs in, a courier tops up, or a retail customer draws a session <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-025\">S-025</button>. The second driver is the operational engine that closes that gap: the machinery that decides <strong>when to buy, when to charge, and what to price</strong>, so a cheap average landed cost becomes a cheap marginal cost at the moment of each interaction <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-025\">S-025</button>. This is where the domain's distinctive formula-and-code palette lives — the load-reading, price-setting, dispatch-solving logic that the two mechanisms below make concrete.</p>","children":["D2.d2.m1","D2.d2.m2"]},"D2.d2.m1":{"id":"D2.d2.m1","level":4,"parent":"D2.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","Load, demand & dispatch","Reading the load curve"],"title":"Mechanism 2.1 — Reading the load curve","body":"<p>Demand is not flat, and <strong>the shape of the curve is the whole game</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-026\">S-026</button>. Two patterns dominate, and both are read off the network-average kW drawn, normalised to peak = 100.</p><p>The daily curve has two peaks. A sharp morning ramp runs 06:00–09:00, driven by fleet pre-positioning plus commuter charging. A taller, longer evening peak runs 17:00–21:00, stacking fleet recharge, courier surge, and retail on top of one another. The trough sits at 00:00–05:00 — the hours when landed cost is lowest and demand is thinnest at the same time <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-026\">S-026</button>. The economic opportunity is precisely <strong>the gap between the two</strong>: expensive power meets peak demand in the evening, cheap power meets no demand overnight.</p><p>The seasonal curve, indexed to Jan = 100, has two ridges that make the problem worse. A cooling-driven summer peak (Jun–Aug) lands in the tropical metros, where grid prices spike exactly when air-conditioning load does. A Q4 logistics ridge is driven by D3's delivery surge <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-204\">S-204</button>. Neither ridge coincides with a cheap-power window — which is the entire reason <strong>dispatch, not just procurement, is where margin is made or lost</strong>. Reading the curve chains directly into acting on it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-026\">S-026</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Reading the load curve","lines":"Load100 |                          ██ ██ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">90</span> |                    ██  ██ ██ ██ ██ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">75</span> |          ██        ██  ██ ██ ██ ██        ██ ██ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">60</span> |    ██ ██ ██ ██     ██  ██ ██ ██ ██     ██ ██ ██ ██ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">45</span> | ██ ██ ██ ██ ██  ██ ██  ██ ██ ██ ██  ██ ██ ██ ██ ██ ██ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">30</span> | ██ ██ ██ ██ ██  ██ ██  ██ ██ ██ ██  ██ ██ ██ ██ ██ ██    +----------------------------------------------------------      <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">00</span>  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">03</span>  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">06</span>   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">08</span>  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">09</span>   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">17</span> <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">18</span> <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">19</span> <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">20</span>   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">22</span>  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">23</span>   (hour)              morning peak      evening peak"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D2.d2.m2":{"id":"D2.d2.m2","level":4,"parent":"D2.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","Load, demand & dispatch","Dynamic pricing and dispatch optimisation"],"title":"Mechanism 2.2 — Dynamic pricing and dispatch optimisation","body":"<p>Given the curve, the engine does two coupled things off <strong>one margin object</strong>: it prices demand to flatten the peaks, and it dispatches charging and stored energy into the troughs <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-027\">S-027</button>.</p><p>The pricing side sets a per-session price as a base landed cost plus a <strong>congestion term</strong> that rises with local utilisation and a <strong>scarcity term</strong> that rises with the live grid price — then floors the result to protect customer trust and caps it to protect trust the other way. In the formula, util(s,t) ∈ [0,1] is site utilisation, grid(t) is the live wholesale price, and β and γ are tuned per city <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-027\">S-027</button>. The dispatch side solves, over a rolling 24-hour horizon, when to draw from storage versus the grid to minimise landed cost subject to meeting the forecast load <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-027\">S-027</button>.</p><p>The engine pays. Live, peak-to-trough load has flattened by <strong>18 points of the normalised index</strong> versus a flat-tariff baseline, and storage arbitrage captured <strong>$0.019/kWh of additional margin</strong> on the 22% of volume it touches <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-205\">S-205</button>. Crucially, the same engine is what lets Kepler hand D1 and D3 a stable, low internal transfer price: having flattened its own exposure, it can offer the fleet a fixed <strong>$0.094/kWh</strong> and D3 <strong>$0.101/kWh</strong> — both far below the <strong>$0.163 retail benchmark</strong>, and that gap is the marginal-cost reduction the flywheel promised <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-206\">S-206</button>. Dispatch stability chains into the third driver: a network that is economically stable is the precondition for being reliable, and <strong>reliability is where trust is minted</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-027\">S-027</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Dynamic pricing and dispatch optimisation","lines":"price(s,t) = clip(    c_land(t) · (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1</span> + β·util(s,t)) + γ·max(<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0</span>, grid(t) − grid_ref),    p_floor, p_cap)margin(s,t) = price(s,t) − c_land(t) − c_ops(s)"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D2.d3":{"id":"D2.d3","level":3,"parent":"D2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","Reliability & the trust it buys"],"title":"Driver 3 — Reliability & the trust it buys","body":"<p>The third driver of Energy &amp; Charging is the one the standalone financial model cannot see, because reliability shows up as an <strong>absence</strong> — the charge that did not fail, the queue that did not form, the trip the fleet did not have to abort <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-028\">S-028</button>. A DCF prices what happens; reliability's whole value is measured in what does not, so it never lands as a line item. Yet this is precisely how Energy moves the <strong>T</strong> term of the moat, and T is the term with the longest cross-domain reach <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-028\">S-028</button> — the same trust earned at the socket is the trust Payments, Logistics, and the fleet all draw on downstream.</p>","children":["D2.d3.m1","D2.d3.m2"]},"D2.d3.m1":{"id":"D2.d3.m1","level":4,"parent":"D2.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","Reliability & the trust it buys","Uptime as the atomic unit of trust"],"title":"Mechanism 3.1 — Uptime as the atomic unit of trust","body":"<p>Trust in physical infrastructure is not a brand attribute; it is an <strong>empirical frequency</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-029\">S-029</button>. A user trusts the network to the exact degree that it works when they arrive — so we instrument it obsessively rather than assert it.</p><p>The utilization gauge reads the operating health of the estate at a glance. Network uptime sits at <strong>99.2%</strong> against a 99.0% target and an industry field average nearer 96% <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-208\">S-208</button>; session-success — a plug-in that ends in a completed charge — runs at 98.6% <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-208\">S-208</button>. The three-point gap between our uptime and the industry field average is not a bragging right. It is the <strong>raw material of T</strong>: the surplus reliability over what a rider expects elsewhere is exactly what converts into durable trust <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-208\">S-208</button>.</p><p>The cohort data shows why that surplus compounds. A user whose first three sessions all succeeded shows a <strong>4.1× higher 90-day retention</strong> than one who hit an early failed session, and — critically — a <strong>2.3× higher rate of activating the D4 wallet</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-209\">S-209</button>. The failed charge does not just cost one session; it poisons the trust that Payments was going to draw on <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-209\">S-209</button>. Reliability, measured this way, is the atomic unit the rest of the flywheel is built on.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Uptime as the atomic unit of trust","lines":"  NETWORK UPTIME                 SESSION SUCCESS  ┌───────────────┐              ┌───────────────┐  │   ◐ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">99.2</span>%     │              │   ◑ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">98.6</span>%     │  │  ▁▃▅▇█ target  │              │  ▁▃▅▇  target │  │      <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">99.0</span>%    │              │      <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">98.0</span>%    │  └───────────────┘              └───────────────┘     ▲ green                        ▲ green  MEAN QUEUE WAIT (peak)         DC-FAST AVG DELIVERED  ┌───────────────┐              ┌───────────────┐  │   ◕ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3.4</span> min   │              │   ◔ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">141</span> kW    │  │  target ≤<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">5.0</span>  │              │  of <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">150</span> rated │  │      green    │              │   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">94</span>% · green │  └───────────────┘              └───────────────┘"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D2.d3.m2":{"id":"D2.d3.m2","level":4,"parent":"D2.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","Reliability & the trust it buys","Reliability feeds T that Payments (D4) relies on"],"title":"Mechanism 3.2 — Reliability feeds T that Payments (D4) relies on","body":"<p>This is the coupling that justifies housing energy and payments <strong>under one roof</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-030\">S-030</button>. Trust earned at the socket is fungible in the user's mind: the person who has learned that the Kepler charger always works is measurably more willing to let the Kepler wallet hold a balance, auto-pay, and eventually accept a credit line <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-030\">S-030</button>.</p><p>We can trace it in the funnel. Of users who reached <strong>\"high-trust\" status</strong> via a clean charging history, <strong>58% enabled auto-pay within 60 days</strong> versus 29% of the general base, and their D4 <strong>fraud-dispute rate ran 40% lower</strong> — reliable-infrastructure users are, empirically, lower-risk users <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-210\">S-210</button>. Energy is therefore a <strong>T-acquisition channel for Payments</strong>, and it is cheaper than any marketing D4 could run, because the trust is a by-product of a charge the user was going to buy anyway <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-030\">S-030</button>. There is no acquisition spend; the moat term is minted as a side effect of ordinary usage.</p><p>The mechanism chains forward one last time. If reliability is the asset that buys trust, then the <strong>durability of that reliability under a shifting grid</strong> is the thing we must stress-test — which is the fourth driver <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-030\">S-030</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D2.d4":{"id":"D2.d4","level":3,"parent":"D2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","The energy-transition scenario"],"title":"Driver 4 — The energy-transition scenario","body":"<p>The final driver is the ten-year question that hangs over every charging asset the domain will ever build: does Energy's <strong>cost floor and trust ceiling survive a decarbonising, re-pricing grid</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-031\">S-031</button>? Alone among the six domains, its core input — the wholesale price of electricity — is set by forces outside Kepler entirely <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-031\">S-031</button>. We therefore refuse a point forecast, which would pretend to a precision we do not have, and instead model the domain as a tree of grid-price paths, each path mapped to a margin outcome <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-031\">S-031</button>.</p>","children":["D2.d4.m1","D2.d4.m2"]},"D2.d4.m1":{"id":"D2.d4.m1","level":4,"parent":"D2.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","The energy-transition scenario","The scenario tree from grid price to margin"],"title":"Mechanism 4.1 — The scenario tree from grid price to margin","body":"<p>The tree branches on grid-price path → renewables mix → net domain contribution margin, and the headline is not a forecast but a distribution: the <strong>probability-weighted expected margin across the whole tree is +$0.036/kWh</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-211\">S-211</button>. The decisive feature, though, is the shape rather than the average — five of six branches are margin-positive <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-211\">S-211</button>. The single negative branch, *Squeeze* — in which grid prices rise and our PPAs reprice against us — carries only ~6% weight, and it carries so little precisely because the long-dated PPA book and the storage hedge (Mechanism 2.2) are the exact instruments built to collapse it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-211\">S-211</button>. The tail that would sink a standalone charging business is the one we have already bought insurance against.</p><p>The strategically important reading is the second-order one <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-212\">S-212</button>. The two *Grid rises* branches are painful for standalone margin, yet they are actively helpful for the cost-advantage spread: when retail power spikes, our hedged landed cost spikes far less, so the gap we hand to Mobility (D1) and Logistics (D3) actually widens <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-212\">S-212</button>. The domain's cross-domain value is therefore <strong>counter-cyclical to its own P&amp;L</strong> — the branches that hurt the standalone Energy business are the same ones that most help the flywheel <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-212\">S-212</button>. That is why the tree matters strategically and not merely financially: read as a silo, a rising grid is a threat; read as a feeder, it is when the moat term Energy owns pays out hardest to the domains it supplies <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-212\">S-212</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The scenario tree from grid price to margin","lines":"                          ┌─ Renewables &gt;<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">60</span>% ──► margin +$<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.061</span>/kWh   [Green-Cheap]   p≈.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">28</span>       ┌─ Grid falls ─────┤       │  (glut / solar)  └─ Renewables <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">40</span>-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">60</span>% ► margin +$<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.048</span>/kWh   [Green-Base]    p≈.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">17</span> START ┤       │                  ┌─ Storage scales ───► margin +$<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.033</span>/kWh   [Volatile-Win]  p≈.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">22</span>       ├─ Grid volatile ──┤       │  (peaky)         └─ Storage lags ─────► margin +$<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.012</span>/kWh   [Volatile-Thin] p≈.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">13</span>       │       └─ Grid rises ──────┬─ PPAs hold ───────► margin +$<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.007</span>/kWh   [Hedged-Flat]   p≈.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14</span>          (gas / carbon)   └─ PPAs reprice ────► margin −$<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.009</span>/kWh   [Squeeze]       p≈.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">06</span>"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D2.d4.m2":{"id":"D2.d4.m2","level":4,"parent":"D2.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Energy & Charging","The energy-transition scenario","Siting and dispatch as the hedge against the tree"],"title":"Mechanism 4.2 — Siting and dispatch as the hedge against the tree","body":"<p>The tree is not a fate we merely await; the first three drivers are the instruments that <strong>bias us toward its upper branches</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-033\">S-033</button>. Data-led siting (1.1) concentrates the estate where renewables and storage are scaling fastest, tilting the renewables-mix fork in our favour before the price path is even known <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-033\">S-033</button>. Vertical procurement (1.2) locks the PPAs that hold in the *Grid rises* branch, so the very state that punishes an unhedged operator leaves us intact <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-033\">S-033</button>. Dispatch optimisation (2.2) is literally the mechanism that converts a *Volatile-Thin* world into a *Volatile-Win* one by arbitraging the peaks <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-033\">S-033</button>. Reliability (3.x) ensures that whatever branch we land in, the trust output — and therefore the D4 coupling back into the flywheel — is preserved <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-033\">S-033</button>.</p><p>The property this buys is the one we most want from an infrastructure asset facing a decade of grid re-pricing: <strong>every driver in this section is simultaneously an operating lever and a hedge on the transition tree</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-033\">S-033</button>. A lever in the good states, a hedge in the bad ones — the same mechanisms that raise the expected margin also compress the variance around it, which is why the tree's downside is shallow enough to leave five of six branches positive <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-033\">S-033</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"scenario-tree","data":{"root":"10-year grid-price path → renewables mix → net domain contribution margin [S-211]","branches":[{"label":"Squeeze","prob":0.06,"value":"negative margin","note":"Grid prices rise and our PPAs reprice against us — the single negative branch of the six. Carries only ~6% weight because the long-dated PPA book and the storage hedge (Mechanism 2.2) are built precisely to collapse it. [S-211]"},{"label":"Grid rises (hedged)","prob":null,"value":"positive margin; spread widens","note":"Painful for standalone margin, but hedged landed cost spikes far less than retail power, so the cost gap handed to Mobility (D1) and Logistics (D3) widens — the domain's cross-domain value is counter-cyclical to its own P&L. [S-212]"},{"label":"Volatile → Win","prob":null,"value":"positive margin","note":"Dispatch optimisation (Mechanism 2.2) arbitrages the peaks, converting what would be a Volatile-Thin world into a Volatile-Win one. [S-033]"},{"label":"Renewables scale","prob":null,"value":"positive margin","note":"Grid decarbonises and renewables/storage scale on plan; data-led siting (1.1) has already concentrated the estate here. The majority cluster among the five margin-positive branches. [S-211]"}],"caption":"Six-branch tree; five of six branches margin-positive; probability-weighted expected margin +$0.036/kWh. Load-bearing (negative) branch Squeeze shown first. [S-211]"},"evidence_class":"illustrate"},"children":[]},"D3":{"id":"D3","level":2,"parent":"GT","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace"],"title":"Domain 3 — Logistics Marketplace: liquidity is the product","body":"<p>Domain 3 is the only Kepler business whose moat term you can watch move in real time. It owns network liquidity (L) — the probability that, at any given moment in any given cell of any of our 42 cities, a courier and a merchant order can be matched inside the time and price window that both sides will accept. Mobility (D1) owns density, Devices (D5) own breadth, Payments (D4) and Energy (D2) own trust; Logistics owns the term that turns a pile of supply and a pile of demand into a market. And L is the most fragile of the four, because it is not a stock we accumulate but a flow we defend every fifteen minutes. A city can have thousands of couriers and thousands of hungry merchants and still be illiquid — if they are in the wrong places, priced wrong, or matched slowly, the market clears at 61% and both sides quietly churn. Liquidity is not headcount. Liquidity is the product, and everything in this section is a mechanism for manufacturing it.</p><p>The reason Logistics is sequenced third — after Mobility, before the marketplace scales past break-even — is that L is the term with the richest cross-feeds, and it is starved without them. Routing time, the single largest input to match quality, is fed by D1 mobility data: the same 3.1 billion monthly location traces that steer autonomous vehicles give our ETA models the real, congestion-aware travel time between any two points, which no standalone delivery app can match (trace S-301). The courier fleet's marginal energy cost is set by D2: e-bike and van charging runs on Kepler's own network at $0.038/km against a $0.091/km market blended rate, which is the difference between a courier earning a living wage at our take rate and not (S-302). Every payout and every merchant settlement runs cash-free through D4, which is what lets us pay couriers within nine seconds of drop-off and underwrite merchant working-capital advances against observed order flow (S-303). And the matching engine itself — the beating heart of L — is sharpened continuously by D6 models trained on the pooled interaction history of all six domains (S-304). Run Logistics as a standalone marketplace and it is a worse DoorDash. Run it as the liquidity organ of a flywheel and it is a market no standalone can price against.</p><p>Today Logistics is 18% of revenue (0.04/order blended, against a −0.31). It moves L from an indexed 0.38 to a target 0.71 over the plan — measured as fill rate × match-quality × repeat-rate, the composite defined below. The four drivers that follow are the machinery that does it, and they chain: two-sided liquidity is the physics, courier supply and merchant demand are the two pistons, and the matching engine is the crankshaft that converts both into cleared orders.</p>","finding":"None of those facts is the point","finding_full":"<p>What's true. Logistics is 18% of revenue, growing +34% yoy, roughly contribution-neutral today at +€0.04/order. The two-sided funnel leaks hard at the same cliff on both sides. The courier retention curve smiles and the merchant curve flattens high. A professional core of 19% of couriers does 68% of volume. Contribution flips positive only above the batching-density threshold. All of that is real, measured, and — read as a standalone marketplace — describes a competent-but-unremarkable delivery business trailing the category leader on scale.</p><p>What counts. None of those facts is the point. The</p>","children":["D3.d1","D3.d2","D3.d3","D3.d4"]},"D3.d1":{"id":"D3.d1","level":3,"parent":"D3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Two-sided liquidity: the core marketplace dynamic"],"title":"Driver 1 — Two-sided liquidity: the core marketplace dynamic","body":"<p>Liquidity is the reflexive loop the Logistics Marketplace lives or dies inside, and stating it precisely is the whole discipline — not a slogan but the one dynamic every other lever in the domain ultimately routes through <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-036\">S-036</button>. <strong>More couriers online shortens pickup ETAs and cuts unfulfilled orders, which lifts merchant satisfaction and order volume, which densifies the earnings opportunities available per online hour, which pulls still more couriers online.</strong> That is the forward loop, and it compounds. But the same loop runs in reverse just as fast: a thin week thins the other side within two weeks, because couriers and merchants each read a degraded experience and quietly reallocate their next shift or next order elsewhere <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-036\">S-036</button>. The job, therefore, is two things at once — to bias the loop forward at the lowest subsidy cost, and to know, cell by cell and hour by hour, exactly where on the liquidity curve each market sits, because a market near the tipping point and a market already past it demand opposite interventions <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-036\">S-036</button>.</p>","children":["D3.d1.m1","D3.d1.m2"]},"D3.d1.m1":{"id":"D3.d1.m1","level":4,"parent":"D3.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Two-sided liquidity: the core marketplace dynamic","The liquidity composite and the two-sided funnel"],"title":"Mechanism 1.1 — The liquidity composite and the two-sided funnel","body":"<p>Liquidity is refused as a single \"orders\" number, because that number hides the two independent conversion pipelines feeding it — and a headline that averages two failing sides can look healthy while both legs rot <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-037\">S-037</button>. Instead both sides are instrumented as a two-sided conversion funnel, and the shape of each side tells us precisely which piston is misfiring rather than merely that the engine is down <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-305\">S-305</button>.</p><p>The funnel makes the pathology legible. The courier side hemorrhages between \"first shift\" and \"4+ shifts\" — the exact moment a new courier learns whether the app can actually feed them enough well-paid jobs to bother staying. That <strong>58%→39% cliff is a liquidity problem masquerading as a retention problem</strong>: couriers churn not because onboarding is hard but because the market was thin the week they tried it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-037\">S-037</button>. The merchant side leaks worst from \"first order taken\" to \"10+ orders,\" and for the exactly symmetric reason — a restaurant that lists and then waits twenty minutes for a courier on its first lunch rush concludes we don't work, and never gives us a second service <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-037\">S-037</button>.</p><p>Both cliffs are the same cliff seen from two sides, which is the entire insight of two-sided liquidity: you cannot fix one funnel without the other, because each side's drop-off is the other side's thinness reflected back. That is why the composite is built as a product, not a sum: <strong>L = fill-rate × match-quality × repeat-rate</strong> is deliberately multiplicative so that improving one leg while starving another does not move it — the metric refuses to reward a lopsided fix <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-306\">S-306</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"two-sided-funnel","data":{"left":{"name":"Courier funnel","rows":[["Onboarded",100,100],["First shift",58,58],["4+ shifts",39,39]]},"right":{"name":"Merchant funnel","rows":[["Listed",100,100],["First order taken",58,58],["10+ orders",39,39]]},"cliff_index":2},"evidence_class":"illustrate"},"children":[]},"D3.d1.m2":{"id":"D3.d1.m2","level":4,"parent":"D3.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Two-sided liquidity: the core marketplace dynamic","Cohort retention as the liquidity truth serum"],"title":"Mechanism 1.2 — Cohort retention as the liquidity truth serum","body":"<p>Because the funnel is only a snapshot of who is converting now, the business is governed on cohort-retention curves — the honest, un-gameable record of whether each side actually stuck over time <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-038\">S-038</button>. The shapes of those curves are as diagnostic as the numbers, and two facts govern the entire plan.</p><p>First, the merchant curve flattens high. Merchants that survive their first month churn at <strong>under 3% a month</strong>, because a restaurant that has integrated Kepler into its lunch service faces real operational switching cost and, critically, because D4 working-capital advances — settled against the flow Kepler already observes — make Kepler a lender as well as a channel, which is a far stickier relationship than a delivery contract <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-038\">S-038</button>. That flat tail is where merchant lifetime value actually lives. Second, the courier curve smiles: it decays first, then stabilizes around a hard core of professional couriers doing 30+ hours a week who account for <strong>68% of delivered volume from just 19% of the retained cohort</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-307\">S-307</button>.</p><p>These two shapes dictate opposite tactics. For merchants, win month one and the curve holds itself — the investment belongs at the front. For couriers, over-invest in the professional core and treat the casual tail as elastic surge capacity, not as the base to be retained. Managing the two sides identically — the standalone-marketplace default — wastes subsidy on couriers who were always going to churn and under-serves merchants in the single month that decides their lifetime <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-038\">S-038</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Cohort retention as the liquidity truth serum","lines":"COHORT RETENTION — % of month-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0</span> cohort still active   (mature-market blend) Courier cohorts                         Merchant cohorts100 ●                                   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">100</span> ●    ●●                                      ●●● <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">60</span>   ●●●___                             <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">75</span>      ●●●●●●____________  ← merchant curve       ▔▔▔▔▔●●●●________  ← smiles up          flattens HIGH &amp; FLAT <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">28</span>          ▔▔▔▔▔▔▔●●●●●●  ← courier      <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">41</span>             ▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔                  ▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔▔     M0  M1  M2  M3  M4  M5  M6            M0  M1  M2  M3  M4  M5  M6"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D3.d2":{"id":"D3.d2","level":3,"parent":"D3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Courier supply: manufacturing the sell side"],"title":"Driver 2 — Courier supply: manufacturing the sell side","body":"<p>Couriers are the sell side of the logistics marketplace, and Kepler's thesis is that this side is not found, it is manufactured order by order. Couriers are <strong>half the market and the more volatile half</strong>, because their participation is priced by the hour against every other earning option in the city <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-039\">S-039</button> — a rider who could drive for mobility, run an errand, or simply stay home re-prices their labor every hour, so supply that was online at 6pm is gone by 7 unless something on the screen holds it. Supply is therefore not recruited once; it is summoned, and that is why the courier-facing surface — the app in a rider's hand — is treated as a first-class strategic asset, not a UI afterthought <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-039\">S-039</button>. The two mechanisms below are how the summoning is engineered: the job-offer screen that makes a single order legibly worth accepting in the seconds a courier gives it, and the elasticity model that prices the marginal hour so Kepler never subsidizes the whole population to solve a problem that lives only in the tail.</p>","children":["D3.d2.m1","D3.d2.m2"]},"D3.d2.m1":{"id":"D3.d2.m1","level":4,"parent":"D3.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Courier supply: manufacturing the sell side","The job-offer surface: earning legible in one screen"],"title":"Mechanism 2.1 — The job-offer surface: earning legible in one screen","body":"<p>A courier decides to <strong>accept or decline in under four seconds</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-040\">S-040</button>. Everything that determines whether L — marketplace liquidity — holds has to be legible inside that window: the guaranteed payout, the honest ETA, the surge multiplier, and the batching. The live in-app job-offer screen and the push that precedes it are real production copy <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-308\">S-308</button>, and every element on it is a liquidity lever with a specific cross-feed behind it.</p><ul><li>The <strong>€14.20 is guaranteed, not estimated</strong> — the courier is paid that number even if the drop runs long. That guarantee is only underwritable because D4 (payments) pays out in nine seconds and D6 (the data platform) predicts route time tightly enough that guarantee variance stays at ±7% <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-040\">S-040</button>. A standalone app that cannot bound its own route-time variance cannot promise a hard number without bleeding on every long drop.</li><li>The \"~22 min\" and \"5.4 km\" are <strong>honest because D1 mobility traces give congestion-real ETAs</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-309\">S-309</button>. A competitor quoting optimistic times trains its own couriers to distrust the app — which is precisely the 58%→39% funnel cliff reproduced in miniature at the level of a single offer <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-040\">S-040</button>.</li><li>The \"bike at 88%\" line ties to <strong>D2 (energy)</strong>: the app only offers a battery-heavy multi-stop batch to a courier whose charge — on Kepler's network, at Kepler's cost — can actually complete it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-040\">S-040</button>. The batch that most improves liquidity is only ever shown to the courier who can finish it.</li><li>The \"acceptance 94% · keeps Priority tier\" line is the <strong>incentive spine</strong>: acceptance rate is the courier's stake in the matching engine (Driver 3), surfaced to them at the exact moment the decision is made <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-040\">S-040</button>.</li></ul><p>Read together, the screen is the flywheel compressed into four seconds. Four separate domains — D1, D2, D4, D6 — each pay into one accept/decline decision, and a single-vertical courier app cannot reproduce that offer because it touches none of those four surfaces at once.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The job-offer surface: earning legible in one ","lines":"┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐│  PUSH (lock screen)                            ││  Kepler Courier · now                          ││  ⚡ Surge <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1.6</span>× near you — <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span> stacked orders,    ││     est. €<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14.20</span> <span class=\"k\">for</span> ~<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">22</span> min. Tap to grab.      │└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘┌──────────────────────────────────────────────┐│   NEW OFFER            ⏱ 12s to accept   ●●●○  ││                                                ││   €<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14.20</span>   guaranteed          SURGE <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1.6</span>× ⚡   ││   ───────────────────────────────────────────  ││   BATCH · <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span> stops              Pickup <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">4</span> min     ││                                                ││   ①  Nonna's Kitchen · Jl. Kemang    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.9</span> km    ││   ②  Green Bowl · same block         +<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.3</span> km    ││   ③  → <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span> drops, all within <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">2.1</span> km               ││                                                ││   Route: <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">5.4</span> km · ~<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">22</span> min · paid on drop        ││   Charged &amp; ready: bike at <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">88</span>% 🔋               ││   ───────────────────────────────────────────  ││   Your acceptance: <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">94</span>% ·  keeps Priority tier   ││                                                ││   [   DECLINE   ]        [   ACCEPT  €<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14.20</span>  ]  │└──────────────────────────────────────────────┘"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D3.d2.m2":{"id":"D3.d2.m2","level":4,"parent":"D3.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Courier supply: manufacturing the sell side","Supply elasticity and the cost of the marginal hour"],"title":"Mechanism 2.2 — Supply elasticity and the cost of the marginal hour","body":"<p>Kepler models the marginal cost of an online courier-hour by tier, and the table is <strong>the supply curve made operational</strong> — the same model that prices surge in Driver 4 <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-041\">S-041</button>. It splits supply into two populations that behave nothing alike:</p><ul><li>The <strong>professional core is inelastic and cheap</strong> — it comes online regardless of small price moves and clears at low marginal cost.</li><li>The <strong>casual tail is elastic and expensive</strong>, summoned online only when demand spikes past what the core can clear.</li></ul><p>The strategy reads straight off the table <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-310\">S-310</button>. Protect the core's effective pay at almost any cost, because losing 1% of them costs disproportionate volume; and use the casual tail's high elasticity as a supply valve — dial surge to pull it online for the roughly two hours a day it is actually needed, and let it recede otherwise. The failure mode designed against is <strong>subsidizing the whole population to solve a problem that lives in the tail</strong>, which is how standalone marketplaces burn cash into a thin market: they raise the price everyone sees to summon the few who were the constraint.</p><p>The resulting cost advantage is structural, not promotional. Because D2 lowers the core's real energy cost and D4 lowers their payout friction to zero, <strong>Kepler's core clears at €9.10/hr where a competitor renting charging and paying weekly clears near €11.20</strong> — a 19% supply-cost advantage that widens L at equal price <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-041\">S-041</button>. The cross-feeds are not a story told after the fact; they show up as a fixed discount on the single largest variable cost in the marketplace.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["Supply tier","% of couriers","% of volume","Elasticity to +10% pay","Marginal cost/online-hr","Churn if pay −5%"],"rows":[["Professional core (30h+)","19%","68%","+2% hours","€9.10","1.1%"],["Regular (10–30h)","34%","26%","+11% hours","€10.40","6.8%"],["Casual/surge tail (<10h)","47%","6%","+38% hours","€13.90","22%"]],"negCols":[0]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D3.d3":{"id":"D3.d3","level":3,"parent":"D3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","The matching engine: converting both sides into cleared orders"],"title":"Driver 3 — The matching engine: converting both sides into cleared orders","body":"<p>Supply and demand do not clear themselves. The matching engine is the <strong>crankshaft</strong> of the logistics marketplace — the code that, every few seconds, scans every open order and every idle courier inside a cell and decides who gets what <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-042\">S-042</button>. Its objective function is not raw delivery speed but the <strong>liquidity composite</strong>: the engine is scored on the health of the market it is clearing, not on the convenience of any single order. That distinction is the entire design. A naive nearest-courier matcher looks fine at low load and collapses under surge, because greedy local matches strand the distant orders no idle courier is ever offered — so the engine has to optimize the market as a system, not each order in isolation <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-042\">S-042</button>.</p>","children":["D3.d3.m1","D3.d3.m2"]},"D3.d3.m1":{"id":"D3.d3.m1","level":4,"parent":"D3.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","The matching engine: converting both sides into cleared orders","Batch-optimal assignment, not greedy nearest"],"title":"Mechanism 3.1 — Batch-optimal assignment, not greedy nearest","body":"<p>On each short dispatch tick the engine does not match orders one at a time. It <strong>batches</strong> every open order and every idle courier in the cell into a single bipartite assignment problem, then solves it for a blended cost — ETA, batching gain, courier fairness, and predicted acceptance — so the whole cell clears together rather than order-by-order <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-043\">S-043</button>. The pseudocode is the actual shape of the production loop, not an illustration of it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-311\">S-311</button>.</p><p>Four cross-feeds are load-bearing inside that one function, and each is a different domain wired straight into the matcher:</p><ul><li><strong>D1_travel_time</strong> replaces straight-line distance with congestion-real ETA — the single biggest match-quality gain, worth <strong>+9pts of fill rate</strong> in dense cells <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-312\">S-312</button>.</li><li><strong>D6_accept_model</strong> predicts, per courier per batch, the probability of acceptance, so each job is offered to the courier most likely to take it and do it well — cutting the decline-and-reoffer churn that otherwise adds <strong>40–90s of latency</strong> to an order <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-043\">S-043</button>.</li><li><strong>D2_energy_ok</strong> refuses to hand a courier a batch their remaining charge cannot finish, so an accepted job is a completable one <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-043\">S-043</button>.</li><li><strong>fairness_debt</strong> protects the professional core's earnings from being starved by the optimizer — the term a standalone matcher lacks, and the reason our core churns at <strong>1.1% not 6%</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-043\">S-043</button>.</li></ul><p>Strip out any one of the four and the objective stops describing the market: the batch is precisely what lets ETA, acceptance, energy, and fairness be priced against each other in a single solve rather than fought over one greedy match at a time <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-043\">S-043</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Batch-optimal assignment, not greedy nearest","lines":"<span class=\"c\"># DISPATCH TICK  — runs every Δt = 6s per city celldef match(cell, t):    orders   = open_orders(cell, t)          # unassigned + newly ready    couriers = available(cell, t)            # idle + finishing-soon (D1 ETA)    if liquidity_index(cell) &lt; THIN:         # thin-market guard        raise_surge(cell)                    # → Driver 4, pulls casual tail    # 1. candidate batches: stack drops that share route corridors    batches = build_batches(orders, max_stops=3, detour_cap=0.35)    # 2. cost matrix over (courier c, batch b)    for c in couriers:      for b in batches:        eta   = D1_travel_time(c.loc, b.route, t)     # congestion-real        p_acc = D6_accept_model(c, b, surge(cell))    # learned propensity        soc   = D2_energy_ok(c.vehicle, b.route)      # charge sufficient?        fair  = fairness_debt(c)                      # under-served core ↑        cost[c][b] = (w1*eta - w2*batch_gain(b)                      - w3*p_acc - w4*fair) / soc_ok(soc)    # 3. solve assignment (Hungarian / auction) minimizing total cost    assign = min_cost_matching(cost)    for (c,b) in assign:        offer(c, b, guaranteed_pay(b, surge(cell)))   # → courier app 2.1        # payout on drop settled instantly via D4    return unmatched(orders, assign)          # roll to next tick</span>"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D3.d3.m2":{"id":"D3.d3.m2","level":4,"parent":"D3.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","The matching engine: converting both sides into cleared orders","The engine as the compounding surface"],"title":"Mechanism 3.2 — The engine as the compounding surface","body":"<p>The matcher is where the flywheel compounds <strong>fastest</strong>, because the engine's own output is its next input: every completed offer and every declined offer is a labeled training example fed straight back to D6 <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-044\">S-044</button>. Match quality this quarter trains the acceptance model that raises match quality next quarter — a closed loop, not a one-time gain <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-313\">S-313</button>.</p><p>This is the mechanism by which <strong>L stops being a subsidy we buy and becomes a moat we own</strong>. A competitor can match our courier pay for a week, but cannot match a model trained on <strong>340 million dispatch decisions per month</strong> across six correlated domains — the data is the asset, and it is not for sale <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-044\">S-044</button>. The proof is in the spread: the gap between our fill rate and a well-funded standalone's has widened from <strong>4pts to 11pts over eight quarters</strong> at equal courier pay — not because we spend more, but because the engine has learned more <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-314\">S-314</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D3.d4":{"id":"D3.d4","level":3,"parent":"D3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Merchant demand and density: the buy side and the geometry"],"title":"Driver 4 — Merchant demand and density: the buy side and the geometry","body":"<p>Supply is one piston; <strong>demand is the other, and it carries a spatial dimension supply does not</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-045\">S-045</button>. A courier can be re-routed, but a merchant is a fixed point on the map, and the density of merchants and orders inside a given cell is what decides whether batching — the single biggest efficiency lever in the whole logistics network — is even geometrically possible. Thin, spread-out demand cannot be batched: every drop sits too far from the next for one trip to carry two, so it stays expensive to serve at any courier count you throw at it. Dense demand is the opposite — self-lubricating. The same geography that concentrates orders into a tight cell is what lets each courier trip absorb more of them, so density is not a nice-to-have on the buy side; it is the precondition the entire cost structure hangs on.</p>","children":["D3.d4.m1","D3.d4.m2"]},"D3.d4.m1":{"id":"D3.d4.m1","level":4,"parent":"D3.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Merchant demand and density: the buy side and the geometry","Density as the batching multiplier"],"title":"Mechanism 4.1 — Density as the batching multiplier","body":"<p>The mechanism is a threshold, not a slope. <strong>Below a critical order density the routing engine cannot stack drops</strong>, so every order consumes a whole courier trip end to end; <strong>above it, three drops share one trip and effective supply triples without a single extra courier being added</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-046\">S-046</button>. Kepler manages its cities explicitly against that line, sorting cells by where they sit relative to the batching threshold rather than by raw order count.</p><p>That non-linearity is the whole strategy <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-315\">S-315</button>. The jump from an \"approaching\" cell to a \"liquid\" one flips contribution from negative to positive on the strength of the batching multiplier — not on any price change, not on a better courier deal, purely on the geometry crossing the threshold. Because the gain is a step function, the growth playbook inverts: it is not \"add cities\" but <strong>\"concentrate demand within a city until its cells cross the batching threshold, then widen\"</strong> — a land-and-densify motion rather than a land-grab <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-316\">S-316</button>.</p><p>This is where the flywheel does real work. Kepler does not have to guess which cells can support density before it spends a euro of merchant acquisition, because it reads D1 mobility data to see exactly which cells already carry the foot traffic to sustain it. Mobility has already mapped the demand geography of all 42 cities, so Logistics launches into pre-validated dense cells instead of guessing — a cross-domain advantage no single-vertical courier network can reproduce <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-046\">S-046</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["City density tier","Orders/km²/hr","Avg stops/batch","Effective courier multiplier","Contribution/order"],"rows":[["Sub-critical (launch)","< 8","1.1","1.0×","−€0.61"],["Approaching","8–18","1.6","1.5×","−€0.09"],["Liquid","18–40","2.3","2.2×","+€0.34"],["Dense/core","> 40","2.8","2.7×","+€0.71"]],"negCols":[4]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D3.d4.m2":{"id":"D3.d4.m2","level":4,"parent":"D3.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Logistics Marketplace","Merchant demand and density: the buy side and the geometry","Surge as the equilibrium regulator"],"title":"Mechanism 4.2 — Surge as the equilibrium regulator","body":"<p>When demand spikes past the supply that is actually online, <strong>price is the only fast lever</strong> — surge pulls the elastic casual tail online (Driver 2) and, secondarily, rations demand down toward what the network can clear <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-047\">S-047</button>. The supply–demand equilibrium chart is the control surface the surge engine reads before it acts <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-317\">S-317</button>.</p><p>Read it left to right. At the pre-surge point ○, peak demand D_peak sits far to the right of base supply S₀, and S₀ is nearly vertical because the inelastic core of couriers will not add hours for a small bump. So the market cannot clear: <strong>fill collapses to 71%, ETAs blow out, and both the merchant funnel and the eater funnel start leaking within the hour</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-317\">S-317</button>. Surge shifts supply to S₁ by paying the elastic tail enough to come online, moving the clearing point to ★ at <strong>96% fill</strong>.</p><p>The engine's `raise_surge` call (Mechanism 3.1) is literally walking this curve — it reads the Driver-2 elasticity table and chooses the smallest multiplier that reaches ★. The two failure modes bound the search: set surge too low and the market stays illiquid; set it too high and you over-pay the inelastic core for hours they would have worked anyway while rationing away demand you actually wanted. The flywheel tilts the whole curve in Kepler's favour. Because the casual tail charges on D2's network and is paid instantly by D4, Kepler can pull that tail online at a lower multiplier than a standalone competitor can — <strong>cheaper surge for equal fill is a direct L advantage</strong>, feeding the L term in the moat identity M = D × B × L × T <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-318\">S-318</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Surge as the equilibrium regulator","lines":"SUPPLY–DEMAND EQUILIBRIUM  (single cell, lunch rush) pay/                     S₀ (base supply, inelastic core) order  │  D_peak            S₁ (with <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1.6</span>× surge → casual tail online)  €     │   \\                / <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">16</span> ────│────\\──────────────/─── surge pulls S₀→S₁, <span class=\"k\">new</span> clear at ★        │     \\            /★  ← liquid equilibrium (fill <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">96</span>%) <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">12</span> ────│──────\\────●─────/──────  ○ = pre-surge: D_peak &gt;&gt; S₀,        │        \\  ○    /            fill collapses to <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">71</span>%, ETAs blow out  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">8</span> ────│─────────\\────/────────── S₀ nearly vertical: core won't        │           \\  /              add hours <span class=\"k\">for</span> small pay bumps        └────────────╳──────────────────── orders/hr →                pre-surge gap"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D4":{"id":"D4","level":2,"parent":"GT","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech"],"title":"Domain 4 — Payments & Fintech: trust is the product, monetization is the by-product","body":"<p>Domain 4 is the only domain in the flywheel that moves trust (T) as its primary lever and converts moat strength into cash. Every other domain manufactures interactions, breadth, or liquidity and hopes trust follows; Payments manufactures trust deliberately, prices it, and sells it back to the rest of the platform. In the moat identity M = D × B × L × T, Payments is the term-owner for T and the co-owner — with D6 — of the mechanism that turns a high M into revenue. That dual role is why the register of this section is different from the others: it is written half as a trust-engineering document and half as a monetization thesis, because at Kepler those are the same document read from two ends.</p><p>The governing thought insists that Payments is not a business; it is a closing device. Mobility (D1) generates the densest behavioural data in the company but cannot underwrite anything on its own; Logistics (D3) has the liquidity but no balance sheet; Devices (D5) and the Data/AI platform (D6) generate signals but do not touch money. Payments is the domain that (a) closes the loop — it lets D1 and D3 run cash-free, which raises interaction density and network liquidity by removing the friction of cash handling; (b) underwrites on cross-domain behaviour — it prices credit off D1 mobility patterns and D3 courier-reliability data that no bank can see; and (c) consumes fraud signals from D6 — which are themselves fed by D1's location telemetry and D5's device fingerprints. So Payments moves T for the whole platform, and in doing so it is fed by four other domains and feeds all six. It is the most coupled domain in the flywheel, which is exactly why running it as a standalone fintech P&amp;L — the conglomerate reflex — destroys most of its value. Trace S-400 anchors the claim: a payment at Kepler is worth measurably more than the same payment at a monoline PSP because it arrives pre-scored by five other domains.</p><p>Payments is also the fastest-growing domain in the company, +58% yoy, against a blended −$1.1bn EBIT and a ~35% conglomerate discount. That growth is not the thesis. The thesis is that the growth is sequenced — it only exists because D1 and D3 reached interaction scale first, and it only compounds because every payment it processes writes back into the moat that D6 curates. What follows is four drivers, each chaining into the next: the rails move the money, the credit engine underwrites the money, trust/fraud/compliance protects the money, and monetization/interchange extracts the money — and each driver hands its output to the one after it.</p>","finding_full":"<p>What's true. Payments is the fastest-growing domain (+58% yoy), it now earns most of its gross profit from durable, un-capped layers (S-413), and its per-interaction contribution has already turned positive (S-416). Interchange is legally near-zero across half of Kepler's TPV (S-412), so the standalone \"payments company\" framing is not just incomplete — it is impossible in these markets. On a monoline basis Kepler Payments would trail a focused regional PSP on rate and a focused lender on scale.</p><p>What counts. None of the durable margin exists without the other five domains. The credit engine u</p>","children":["D4.d1","D4.d2","D4.d3","D4.d4"]},"D4.d1":{"id":"D4.d1","level":3,"parent":"D4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","The payments rails: the substrate that makes every other domain cash-free"],"title":"Driver 1 — The payments rails: the substrate that makes every other domain cash-free","body":"<p>Payments is not a business Kepler runs for its own margin; it is the <strong>plumbing that makes every other domain cash-free</strong>. The rails are four concrete pieces of physical-world money movement — the ledger, the PSP and scheme connections, the KYC gate, and the settlement engine <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-050\">S-050</button>. Run them slow, fragmented, or per-domain and the flywheel leaks: every domain rebuilds its own money-movement stack and the shared trust signal never accumulates in one place <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-050\">S-050</button>. The strategic claim of Driver 1 is that <strong>one ledger for all six domains is worth more than six optimised ledgers</strong>, because the value is in the join, not in any single flow <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-050\">S-050</button>.</p>","children":["D4.d1.m1","D4.d1.m2","D4.d1.m3"]},"D4.d1.m1":{"id":"D4.d1.m1","level":4,"parent":"D4.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","The payments rails: the substrate that makes every other domain cash-free","A single unified ledger as the system of record"],"title":"Mechanism 1.1 — A single unified ledger as the system of record","body":"<p>Kepler runs <strong>one double-entry ledger that every domain posts into</strong>: a ride from D1, a charge from D2, a delivery payout to a D3 courier, a device instalment from D5 — all land as entries against the same account graph <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-051\">S-051</button>. This is the mechanism that lets Payments see the whole customer. A rider who also couriers and leases a device is <strong>one node with three revenue streams and one risk profile</strong>, not three anonymous flows in three separate systems <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-051\">S-051</button>.</p><p>The design decision is recorded in trace S-401: the ledger is append-only, event-sourced, and the source of truth for both money movement and the behavioural features D6 later consumes <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-051\">S-051</button>. That dual role is the load-bearing choice — the same write that moves money also emits a feature, so the system of record and the training-data source are one artefact rather than two that must be reconciled.</p><p>The nodes in the architecture converge in a fixed order, and each earns its place. The INGRESS API normalises every domain's payment intent into one schema, so six payment shapes become one. The RISK node calls D6 in-line against the fraud model on a ~40ms budget. The KYC/KYB GATE enforces tiered identity — tier 0 anonymous wallet top-up through tier 3 full underwriting-grade KYC — so the identity bar scales with the exposure. The <strong>UNIFIED LEDGER is the join point</strong> where all six domains finally meet in one account graph <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-051\">S-051</button>.</p><p>The FEATURE STORE bridge is what makes Payments a <strong>contributor to the moat rather than a consumer of it</strong>. Trace S-402 calls the feature-store write-back the single most under-valued line in the architecture — it is how a payment becomes training data, and therefore how Domain 4 feeds the D term of the moat instead of merely spending it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-051\">S-051</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"A single unified ledger as the system of recor","lines":"KEPLER PAYMENTS ARCHITECTURE (rails, ledger, PSPs, KYC)  D1 Mobility ──┐                                    ┌── Card Schemes (Visa/MC/local)  D2 Energy ────┤                                    ├── Local rails (UPI/PIX/PayNow/GrabPay)  D3 Logistics ─┼─►  [ INGRESS API ]  ─►  [ RISK ]   ├── Acquiring banks (per-region)  D5 Devices ───┤        │                  │        └── Bank-transfer / RTP networks  D6 signals ───┘        ▼                  ▼                    [ KYC / KYB GATE ] ─► [ UNIFIED LEDGER ]  ◄──► [ FEATURE STORE → D6 ]                         │  tiers <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0</span>–<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span>         │  event-sourced                         ▼                    ▼                    [ IDENTITY GRAPH ]   [ SETTLEMENT ENGINE ] ─► [ PAYOUTS / INTERCHANGE CAPTURE ]                                              │                                              ▼                                    [ RECONCILIATION + REG REPORTING (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14</span> countries) ]"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D4.d1.m2":{"id":"D4.d1.m2","level":4,"parent":"D4.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","The payments rails: the substrate that makes every other domain cash-free","PSP orchestration and local-rail routing"],"title":"Mechanism 1.2 — PSP orchestration and local-rail routing","body":"<p>No single scheme covers 14 countries economically, so Kepler <strong>orchestrates across rails rather than committing to one</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-052\">S-052</button>. It routes across card schemes, local instant-payment rails — UPI in India, PIX in Brazil, PayNow in Singapore — and bank-transfer/RTP networks, sending each transaction to the <strong>cheapest rail that clears the risk bar</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-052\">S-052</button>.</p><p>The mechanism chains directly out of 1.1. Because the ledger is unified, the router makes a portfolio decision rather than a per-transaction one: it will accept slightly higher fraud on a low-margin D3 courier payout routed over a cheap local rail, because the same user's D1 ride history — fed in via the S-402 write-back — collateralises the risk <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-052\">S-052</button>. The risk headroom comes from cross-domain data, not from anything intrinsic to the rail.</p><p>Trace S-403 captures the routing economics. Shifting <strong>22 points of volume from card schemes to local rails cut blended cost-of-payment from 1.9% to 1.3% of TPV</strong> — without raising realised fraud, because the tolerance was bought with data, not paid for in losses <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-052\">S-052</button>. Six optimised ledgers could not make this trade: none of them would be holding the ride history that underwrites the courier payout, so each would price the local rail on its own thin flow and reject it.</p>","children":[]},"D4.d1.m3":{"id":"D4.d1.m3","level":4,"parent":"D4.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","The payments rails: the substrate that makes every other domain cash-free","Cash-free closure of D1 and D3"],"title":"Mechanism 1.3 — Cash-free closure of D1 and D3","body":"<p>Here Driver 1 hands off to the flywheel. Once the rails are unified and cheap, Kepler can make mobility and logistics <strong>cash-free</strong> — no driver handling notes, no courier reconciling coins <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-053\">S-053</button>. This is the first cross-domain coupling, and it moves two different moat terms at once rather than one.</p><p>Removing cash raises D1's <strong>interaction density (D)</strong>, because more low-value rides become viable when there is no cash to fumble, and it raises D3's <strong>network liquidity (L)</strong>, because couriers get paid instantly and stay on the platform <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-053\">S-053</button>. Trace S-404 measures both: in the six cities where cash was fully removed, <strong>D1 ride frequency rose 11% and D3 courier churn fell 9pp</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-053\">S-053</button>.</p><p>Neither number belongs to Payments' P&amp;L, which is precisely the point. Payments spent margin to buy density and liquidity for other domains, and the moat identity M = D × B × L × T rose even though Domain 4's standalone contribution looked flat <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-053\">S-053</button>. <strong>A conglomerate scorecard would have killed this trade</strong> — it would see a business burning margin on flows it does not book — while a flywheel scorecard sees two terms of the product lifting together, which is the only reading under which the spend makes sense <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-053\">S-053</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D4.d2":{"id":"D4.d2","level":3,"parent":"D4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Credit & underwriting: lending on data no bank can see"],"title":"Driver 2 — Credit & underwriting: lending on data no bank can see","body":"<p>If Driver 1's rails are what make Kepler a payments company, the credit engine is what makes it a <strong>fintech</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-054\">S-054</button>. Driver 2 takes the unified ledger built in Driver 1 and does the one thing an incumbent bank structurally cannot: it underwrites Kepler's 28.4m monthly actives on behavioural collateral — how reliably you ride, charge, deliver, and pay — rather than on a thin or absent credit file <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-054\">S-054</button>. This is the hinge where the moat's trust term T stops being a soft virtue and becomes monetization, because trust that is measured can be lent against <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-054\">S-054</button>. Every clean ride, on-time delivery, and settled charge is a data point the bureau never sees and Kepler already owns — so the collateral is not a document a user brings to the lender, it is the exhaust the platform has been collecting all along.</p>","children":["D4.d2.m1","D4.d2.m2","D4.d2.m3"]},"D4.d2.m1":{"id":"D4.d2.m1","level":4,"parent":"D4.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Credit & underwriting: lending on data no bank can see","Behavioural underwriting off D1 and D3 exhaust"],"title":"Mechanism 2.1 — Behavioural underwriting off D1 and D3 exhaust","body":"<p>The core mechanism is that Kepler scores creditworthiness from platform behaviour that is <strong>exogenous to any credit bureau</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-055\">S-055</button>. A Driver 3 courier with 18 months of on-time deliveries and stable Driver 1 commuting patterns is a demonstrably better risk than her thin bureau file suggests — the file is silent in exactly the place where Kepler is loud <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-055\">S-055</button>. This is the second cross-domain coupling in the flywheel: Payments underwrites on D1 mobility regularity and D3 logistics reliability, two signals a single-vertical lender can never assemble because it touches only one of the surfaces <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-055\">S-055</button>.</p><p>Trace S-405 documents the lift and it is not marginal — adding the cross-domain behavioural features cut the Gini-normalised default rate by 210bps at constant approval, or, read from the other side of the same frontier, raised approvals by 14% at constant loss <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-405\">S-405</button>. The scoring logic physically lives in Driver 6's feature store but is owned, productised, and priced by Driver 4 — D6 supplies the substrate, D4 owns the P&amp;L <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-055\">S-055</button>.</p><p>Trace S-406 is the query itself, and the load-bearing detail is the thick_file flag: a user is \"thick\" not because a bureau holds data on them but because Kepler does, across domains <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-406\">S-406</button>. That single boolean is the entire underwriting moat compressed to one line of the scoring query.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Behavioural underwriting off D1 and D3 exhaust","lines":"<span class=\"c\">-- S-406: Kepler cross-domain credit score (nightly batch, feature-store backed)WITH mobility AS (   -- D1 signal: regularity + tenure  SELECT user_id,         COUNT(*)                         AS rides_90d,         STDDEV(hour_of_day)              AS commute_regularity,   -- lower = more predictable         DATE_PART('day', NOW() - MIN(ts)) AS tenure_days  FROM d1_rides WHERE ts &gt; NOW() - INTERVAL '90 days'  GROUP BY user_id),logistics AS (       -- D3 signal: earnings stability + reliability  SELECT courier_id AS user_id,         AVG(on_time_flag)::numeric(4,3)  AS on_time_rate,         STDDEV(daily_earnings)           AS earnings_vol,         SUM(completed_jobs)              AS jobs_90d  FROM d3_courier_jobs WHERE ts &gt; NOW() - INTERVAL '90 days'  GROUP BY courier_id),payments AS (        -- D4 signal: repayment + ledger balance behaviour  SELECT account_id AS user_id,         AVG(repaid_on_time)::numeric(4,3) AS repay_rate,         MIN(running_balance)              AS min_balance_90d,         COUNT(*) FILTER (WHERE type='chargeback') AS cb_90d  FROM ledger_entries WHERE ts &gt; NOW() - INTERVAL '90 days'  GROUP BY account_id)SELECT u.user_id,       ROUND( 560         + 90 * COALESCE(l.on_time_rate,0.5)          -- reliability         + 70 * LEAST(m.tenure_days/365.0, 1.0)       -- tenure, capped 1yr         - 55 * COALESCE(m.commute_regularity,4)/8.0  -- erratic = riskier         - 40 * LEAST(p.cb_90d, 3)                     -- chargebacks penalised         + 60 * COALESCE(p.repay_rate,0.5)             -- prior repayment       )::int AS kepler_score,       (l.on_time_rate IS NOT NULL AND m.rides_90d &gt; 20) AS thick_fileFROM users uLEFT JOIN mobility m  USING (user_id)LEFT JOIN logistics l USING (user_id)LEFT JOIN payments  p USING (user_id);</span>"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D4.d2.m2":{"id":"D4.d2.m2","level":4,"parent":"D4.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Credit & underwriting: lending on data no bank can see","Working-capital and instalment products that recycle into the flywheel"],"title":"Mechanism 2.2 — Working-capital and instalment products that recycle into the flywheel","body":"<p>The score from Mechanism 2.1 powers three distinct products: courier working-capital advances (D3), device instalments (D5), and consumer BNPL on rides and charges (D1/D2) <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-056\">S-056</button>. The chaining between them is the whole point, not a footnote. A device instalment (D5) puts a proprietary-sensor device — one that raises the moat's data-breadth term B — into the hands of a user who could not have paid upfront, so <strong>credit manufactures moat inputs for other domains</strong> rather than merely earning a spread on the loan <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-056\">S-056</button>.</p><p>Trace S-407 quantifies that feed directly: instalment financing raised D5 device attach among the bottom two income quartiles by 31%, and that attach flows straight into D5's breadth term <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-407\">S-407</button>. Read the sequence and the accounting inverts — credit here is not a yield product to be optimised on its own net-interest-margin; it is a distribution subsidy for the moat, repaid not in interest but in better data across the other five domains <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-056\">S-056</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D4.d2.m3":{"id":"D4.d2.m3","level":4,"parent":"D4.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Credit & underwriting: lending on data no bank can see","Portfolio risk and the loss-provisioning discipline"],"title":"Mechanism 2.3 — Portfolio risk and the loss-provisioning discipline","body":"<p>Underwriting on behaviour is powerful and <strong>pro-cyclical</strong>: the same D1 and D3 signals that predict good times can turn together in a downturn <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-057\">S-057</button>. Driver 2 therefore hands a specific risk downstream to Driver 3 — correlated behavioural default, where a whole cohort deteriorates at once rather than as independent draws <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-057\">S-057</button>.</p><p>Trace S-408 sets the guardrail: exposure is capped per cohort and provisioned against a stressed scenario in which D1 ride frequency and D3 job volume fall together — the very correlation the cross-domain data itself reveals, turned from an edge into a stress input <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-408\">S-408</button>. That is the honest tension at the centre of the thesis: the credit engine's edge and its systemic risk come from the same source <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-057\">S-057</button>. The cross-domain signal that lets Kepler lend where banks cannot is the same signal that co-moves in a downturn, so the discipline is to price and provision for the correlation rather than to pretend the behavioural collateral is diversified when it is not <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-408\">S-408</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"time-series","data":{"unit":"cohort index (pre-stress = 100)","series":[{"name":"D1 ride frequency","dash":false,"pts":[[0,100],[1,99],[2,96],[3,88],[4,79],[5,74],[6,76]]},{"name":"D3 job volume","dash":true,"pts":[[0,100],[1,98],[2,94],[3,85],[4,77],[5,72],[6,75]]}],"mark":{"name":"stress trough — signals fall together [S-408]","x":5,"y":72}},"evidence_class":"illustrate"},"children":[]},"D4.d3":{"id":"D4.d3","level":3,"parent":"D4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Trust, fraud & compliance: the term-owner mechanism for T"],"title":"Driver 3 — Trust, fraud & compliance: the term-owner mechanism for T","body":"<p>Driver 3 is the one driver that <strong>literally moves T in the moat identity M = D × B × L × T</strong> — trust is not an atmosphere here, it is a term with a term-owner. The logic is a ledger of leaks: fraud losses and compliance failures are trust leaking out, and every prevented fraud and every clean audit is trust retained and then <strong>re-lent to all six domains</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-058\">S-058</button>. That re-lending is what makes T a shared asset rather than a cost line inside Payments alone. Crucially, Driver 3 is defensive by construction — it takes the credit exposure opened by Driver 2 and the payment flows opened by Driver 1 and defends both, and it does so <strong>using signals it does not itself generate</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-058\">S-058</button>. That last clause is the whole flywheel in miniature: the term-owner for trust survives on cross-fed data, so lifting T is impossible for any single-vertical competitor that touches only one surface.</p>","children":["D4.d3.m1","D4.d3.m2"]},"D4.d3.m1":{"id":"D4.d3.m1","level":4,"parent":"D4.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Trust, fraud & compliance: the term-owner mechanism for T","Real-time fraud scoring on D6 signals fed by D1 and D5"],"title":"Mechanism 3.1 — Real-time fraud scoring on D6 signals fed by D1 and D5","body":"<p>The fraud engine scores <strong>every transaction inside the ~40ms RISK node</strong> carried over from Driver 1's payment architecture — real-time, in the authorization path, not a nightly batch <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-059\">S-059</button>. What it scores on is the point: its features are the <strong>third and fourth cross-domain couplings</strong> of the payments domain. Fraud signals arrive from D6, the data platform, but D6 does not conjure them — it assembles them from two upstream surfaces no payments competitor can reach:</p><ul><li><strong>D1 location telemetry</strong> — is this ride's device physically where the card says it is? <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-059\">S-059</button></li><li><strong>D5 device fingerprints</strong> — is this the same hardware that onboarded the user? <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-059\">S-059</button></li></ul><p>So a card-not-present transaction that geolocates <strong>300km from the user's D1 device</strong> is scored differently from one that sits inside their normal mobility envelope <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-059\">S-059</button>. The payoff is the rare two-sided win: cross-domain fraud features cut fraud from <strong>18 to 7 basis points of TPV while lowering the false-positive decline rate 22%</strong> — trust up on both sides of the ledger, fewer good customers wrongly blocked and fewer bad ones getting through <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-409\">S-409</button>.</p><p>The configuration encodes the thesis in two design choices <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-410\">S-410</button>. First, the <strong>default response to elevated risk is step-up, not decline</strong> — preserve the good customer, protect trust on the acceptance side. Second, the <strong>trusted_corridor override spends earned trust to remove friction</strong>, the direct mechanical expression of T as a compounding asset: past clean behavior buys future frictionlessness. And the <strong>courier_collusion rule is pure cross-domain</strong> — it can exist only because D3 payouts and D4 funding sources live in one ledger, so a courier paying themselves through a fraudulent order is visible where a siloed competitor sees two unrelated events <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-410\">S-410</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Real-time fraud scoring on D6 signals fed by D","lines":"<span class=\"c\"># S-410: fraud-ops rules config (evaluated after model score, pre-authorization)version: 2026.7model:  name: d6_txn_fraud_v11          # served by D6, features from D1/D5/D4  score_field: p_fraud  latency_budget_ms: 40thresholds:  auto_approve:  { p_fraud: \"&lt; 0.02\" }  step_up_3ds:   { p_fraud: \"0.02 – 0.15\" }   # challenge, don't decline  manual_review: { p_fraud: \"0.15 – 0.45\" }  auto_decline:  { p_fraud: \"&gt;= 0.45\" }rules:  - id: geo_velocity    when: \"d1_last_ping_km_from_txn &gt; 250 AND minutes_since_ping &lt; 30\"    action: step_up_3ds    note: \"physically impossible travel vs D1 telemetry\"  - id: device_swap    when: \"d5_device_fingerprint != account.enrolled_fingerprint\"    action: manual_review  - id: courier_collusion    when: \"d3_payout_to == d4_card_funding_source AND velocity_24h &gt; 8\"    action: hold_and_investigate     # self-dealing loop across D3+D4  - id: new_account_high_ticket    when: \"account.age_days &lt; 7 AND txn.amount &gt; 400\"    action: step_up_3dsoverrides:  trusted_corridor:    when: \"kepler_score &gt; 720 AND thick_file == true\"    action: relax_thresholds         # earned trust buys friction reductionreview_queue: { sla_minutes: 15, staffing: follow_the_sun }</span>"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D4.d3.m2":{"id":"D4.d3.m2","level":4,"parent":"D4.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Trust, fraud & compliance: the term-owner mechanism for T","Compliance, licensing, and the 14-country perimeter"],"title":"Mechanism 3.2 — Compliance, licensing, and the 14-country perimeter","body":"<p>Trust is also <strong>regulatory</strong>, and this mechanism owns that face of T. Kepler holds or passports payment/e-money and lending licences across <strong>14 countries</strong>, and Driver 3 owns the reconciliation and reporting node from the payment architecture <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-060\">S-060</button>. The mechanism chains directly out of 3.1: <strong>the same identity graph that powers fraud scoring powers KYC/KYB and sanctions screening</strong>, so compliance is a reuse of the trust infrastructure, not a parallel cost centre standing beside it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-060\">S-060</button>. The economics of that reuse are measurable — consolidating KYC across domains, so <strong>one verified identity is reused by D1, D3, D4, and D5, cut per-user onboarding cost 38%</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-411\">S-411</button>. But the cost saving is the smaller half. The larger half is that the identity itself becomes a moat asset: a <strong>once-verified Kepler user onboards into every new domain with zero incremental friction</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-411\">S-411</button>. That is the sentence that turns compliance from a tax into a distribution engine — <strong>trust as distribution</strong>, where each domain a user is verified for lowers the activation energy for the next, compounding T across the whole flywheel rather than spending it once.</p>","children":[]},"D4.d4":{"id":"D4.d4","level":3,"parent":"D4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Monetization & interchange: turning a high M into cash"],"title":"Driver 4 — Monetization & interchange: turning a high M into cash","body":"<p>The first three drivers of Payments built trust; this one turns that trust into cash. Kepler takes the flows the earlier drivers defended, underwrote, and made cash-free, and monetises them through four routes — interchange, take-rates, credit yield, and, increasingly, data-adjacent products <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-061\">S-061</button>. The strategic subtlety sits in one distinction: interchange is regulated and varies by region, so the monetization ceiling is set by policy, not by ambition <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-061\">S-061</button>. The durable margin therefore does not live on the swipe — it lives in the parts of the stack regulators do not cap <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-061\">S-061</button>. That single split — the capped swipe on one side, the uncapped trust-products on the other — organises every mechanism below, and it is why Payments' monetization is inseparable from the whole flywheel rather than a rate business run on its own.</p>","children":["D4.d4.m1","D4.d4.m2","D4.d4.m3"]},"D4.d4.m1":{"id":"D4.d4.m1","level":4,"parent":"D4.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Monetization & interchange: turning a high M into cash","Interchange capture within regulated caps"],"title":"Mechanism 4.1 — Interchange capture within regulated caps","body":"<p>Interchange is not one number; it is a patchwork of regional caps, and the monetization model has to be built region-by-region or it breaks <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-062\">S-062</button>. The asymmetry is stark across Kepler's footprint <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-412\">S-412</button>:</p><ul><li>In the EU/EEA the Interchange Fee Regulation sets hard statutory caps — <strong>0.20% on debit and 0.30% on credit</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-412\">S-412</button>. There is almost no rate to play with, so the model must monetize on volume and adjacencies, not on the swipe itself.</li><li>In Singapore and much of South-East Asia there is no hard statutory cap, but scheme-set and competitive pressure lands the effective blended rate at ~0.5–0.9% <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-412\">S-412</button>.</li><li>In India, merchant-side MDR on UPI is effectively zero by policy <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-412\">S-412</button>; monetization here is never interchange — it is credit, float, and value-added services.</li><li>In Brazil, the PIX instant-payment rail carries no interchange while the Central Bank actively compresses card economics <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-412\">S-412</button>; the conclusion is the same as India's.</li></ul><p>Crucially, US-style uncapped credit interchange of ~1.8–2.2% does not exist anywhere in Kepler's markets, so the model must never assume it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-412\">S-412</button>. The implication is the load-bearing one: across roughly <strong>half of Kepler's TPV, interchange is legally near-zero</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-412\">S-412</button>. Monetization therefore cannot rest on the swipe. It has to rest on the trust-adjacent products — credit yield, insurance, merchant lending, data-informed underwriting — that regulators do not cap. This is exactly why Payments cannot be a monoline: in its two largest-by-population markets the swipe is free by law, so the only monetization path is the one that requires the whole flywheel — lending and services priced off cross-domain trust <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-062\">S-062</button>. In the source's own framing, trace S-412 is the reason Driver 2 exists <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-062\">S-062</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D4.d4.m2":{"id":"D4.d4.m2","level":4,"parent":"D4.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Monetization & interchange: turning a high M into cash","Take-rate, float, and the blended monetization stack"],"title":"Mechanism 4.2 — Take-rate, float, and the blended monetization stack","body":"<p>Kepler monetizes across four layers, each carrying a different regulatory exposure, and the point of laying them out as a stack is to show where the margin is actually durable <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-063\">S-063</button>. The swipe-linked layers — interchange and take-rate — sit exposed to the caps of Mechanism 4.1. The trust-linked layers — credit yield and float/services — sit above them, priced off behaviour that regulators do not touch.</p><p>The decisive figure is that the two high-durability layers, credit yield and float/services, already contribute <strong>61% of Payments gross profit despite representing under 40% of TPV</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-413\">S-413</button>. That inversion is the whole point: monetization has already migrated off the regulated swipe and onto the trust-moated products. The stack is not a plan for the future — it is a state Payments has already reached.</p><p>The customer statement is where all four layers are experienced at once, and it is a trust artefact as much as a financial one <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-063\">S-063</button>. The credit score is visible and moving; the APR fell because behaviour earned it — the credit engine talking back to the customer; and the fraud line advertises that protection ran without wrongly blocking her. The statement is where <strong>T, the trust term of the moat, is made felt</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-063\">S-063</button>. And trust, once shown, sells the next product: surfacing the earned-APR line lifted repeat credit uptake <strong>17%</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-414\">S-414</button>. The interface is not decoration laid over the monetization — it is part of the monetization engine.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Take-rate, float, and the blended monetization","lines":"┌───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐│  KEPLER  ·  Monthly Statement            Jul <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">2026</span> · A. Rivera  ││  Account <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">4821</span> ****  ·  Kepler Score <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">731</span> ▲<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">12</span>   Tier <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span> verified  │├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤│  DATE   DESCRIPTION                         AMOUNT     BALANCE  ││  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">07</span>-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">02</span>  D1 Ride · Marina → Bugis           −  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">4.20</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">212.55</span>   ││  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">07</span>-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">03</span>  D3 Courier payout (instant)        + <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">86.40</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">298.95</span>   ││  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">07</span>-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">05</span>  D2 Charge · Node A-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">114</span> · 22kWh     −  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">6.10</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">292.85</span>   ││  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">07</span>-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">09</span>  D5 Device instalment <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span>/<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">12</span>          − <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">21.00</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">271.85</span>   ││  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">07</span>-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14</span>  BNPL repayment · on time           − <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">33.00</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">238.85</span>   ││  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">07</span>-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">16</span>  Cashback · trusted corridor        +  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1.65</span>    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">240.50</span>   │├───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤│  Credit line <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1</span>,<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">200</span>  ·  Used <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">214</span>  ·  Avail <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">986</span>                  ││  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"s\">\"Your on-time history unlocked a lower APR — <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14.9</span>% → <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">12.4</span>%\"</span>   ││  Fraud protection: <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span> step-ups cleared · <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0</span> wrong declines       │└───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D4.d4.m3":{"id":"D4.d4.m3","level":4,"parent":"D4.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Payments & Fintech","Monetization & interchange: turning a high M into cash","The ledger as monetization evidence"],"title":"Mechanism 4.3 — The ledger as monetization evidence","body":"<p>Beneath the statement sits the raw ledger — the same ledger from Driver 1, now read not as a record of flows but as a record of margins <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-064\">S-064</button>. A single day's mixed flows carry very different economics, and the join — one user, many domains — is what makes the portfolio work <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-064\">S-064</button>.</p><p>Read across the user column and the whole monetization thesis appears in miniature. rivera_a and courier_301 each touch three domains in a single day <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-415\">S-415</button>, and the high-margin entries — credit yield running <strong>700–1240 bps</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-415\">S-415</button> — are only underwritable because the low-margin entries, the rides and the jobs, supplied the behavioural collateral that made the underwriting safe. Neither half works alone: a lender without the ride-and-job history cannot price the credit, and the ride-and-job history earns almost nothing until a credit line monetizes it.</p><p>That is the mechanism at its sharpest: <strong>the cheap flows are the moat, the expensive flows are the monetization, and the ledger is the join that makes one pay for the other</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-415\">S-415</button>. The proof point closes the loop. Contribution per interaction inside Payments moved from −0.19 over the trailing period <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-416\">S-416</button> — the clearest single evidence that the flywheel's target path up from the −0.31 blended figure is achievable, and that the path runs straight through Domain 4 <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-416\">S-416</button>. The ledger is where the monetization stops being a story a conglomerate tells and becomes a number a flywheel can show.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["entry_id","ts","user","domain","type","amount","fee_bps","margin_layer"],"rows":[["L-90114","07-14 09:02","rivera_a","D1","ride_debit","−4.20","55","interchange+float"],["L-90115","07-14 09:02","driver_774","D1","driver_payout","+3.55","0","take-rate"],["L-90140","07-14 12:31","rivera_a","D4","bnpl_repay","−33.00","1240","credit_yield"],["L-90162","07-14 18:44","courier_301","D3","wc_advance","+150.00","900","credit_yield"],["L-90163","07-14 18:44","courier_301","D3","job_payout","+86.40","0","take-rate"],["L-90190","07-14 21:10","rivera_a","D5","instalment","−21.00","700","credit_yield"]],"negCols":[5]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D5":{"id":"D5","level":2,"parent":"GT","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware"],"title":"Domain 5 — Devices & Hardware: we sell hardware to harvest data no one else has","body":"<p>Devices is the domain most often misread as the weakest link in the Kepler portfolio, and the misreading is instructive. On a standalone basis it is a low-margin consumer-electronics and industrial-sensor business — a category the market has spent two decades learning to value at single-digit multiples, priced on unit economics, channel, and refresh cycles. Read that way, Devices is a drag: it consumes working capital, it carries inventory risk, it lives and dies on a bill of materials measured in cents, and it will never out-margin a payments network or out-scale a mobility fleet. If Kepler were six businesses, Devices would be the one a focus-minded activist spins out first.</p><p>That is exactly why it is in the portfolio, and exactly why it is misunderstood. In the moat identity</p><p>Devices is the domain that owns data breadth (B) — the width of the sensor manifold that every other domain's models draw from. Density (D) is how often the physical world touches Kepler; breadth (B) is how many independent dimensions it measures each time it does. Mobility (D1) already gives Kepler the densest location-and-behaviour stream on Earth, but density on a narrow set of channels is a shallow moat: a competitor with GPS and a payment rail can approximate most of it. Breadth is what cannot be approximated. When a Kepler device measures road-surface vibration at 400 Hz, ambient particulate load, battery-cell impedance under real load, grip torque on a courier's handlebar, or the acoustic signature of a failing charger relay, it is capturing signal no competitor has instrumented and none can synthesise after the fact. The hardware is not the product. The hardware is the sampling apparatus, and the sample is the product.</p><p>This reframes the whole P&amp;L. We do not sell devices to make money on devices; the gross margin on the hardware is a means of financing a proprietary data-acquisition network that would otherwise sit on Kepler's cost line at full expense. Every unit we ship into a vehicle, a courier's kit, a charging bay, or a merchant's counter is a paid-for sensor node in a fleet that sharpens D6's models — which in turn lower cost and raise trust across D1–D4. The cross-feeds run in every direction, and three matter most: the sensor manifold's breadth (B) directly sharpens the D6 models that improve routing, pricing, and fraud detection; Devices ride physically inside D1 vehicles and D3 courier kit, giving them a distribution channel and power source no standalone device maker enjoys; and D4 payments run on-device, closing the monetisation loop at the point of physical interaction while D2 energy telemetry flows back from every charger and battery we instrument. The rest of this section develops four drivers — the product line, the BOM and margin structure, the supply chain, and the sensor data that is the real product — and shows how each mechanism chains into the next.</p>","finding":"Devices does not exist to make money on devices; it exists…","finding_full":"<p>What's true. Devices is, on its own financials, the portfolio's least impressive business. A 31% hardware gross margin, real inventory and tariff risk, a supply chain with genuine concentration exposure at Penang and Singapore, and a ramp paced by the domains it depends on. Judged as a device company against a focused device company, it trails — exactly as the sum-of-the-parts frame predicts, and exactly the kind of business an activist would tell Kepler to spin out. All of that is true and none of it should be argued away.</p><p>What counts. Devices does not exist to make money on devices; it exis</p>","children":["D5.d1","D5.d2","D5.d3","D5.d4"]},"D5.d1":{"id":"D5.d1","level":3,"parent":"D5","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","The product line: four form factors, one sensor manifold"],"title":"Driver 1 — The product line: four form factors, one sensor manifold","body":"<p>Kepler's device strategy inverts the consumer-electronics playbook. It does not chase new form factors to hit price points or win retail shelf space; it builds the <strong>minimum number of form factors required to place its sensor manifold into the maximum number of high-signal physical contexts</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-067\">S-067</button>. There are exactly four, and they are engineered as one modular platform rather than four separate products — the discipline that lets Devices feed breadth (B) into the moat across mobility, energy, logistics, and payments at once, instead of fragmenting it into four incompatible data streams <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-067\">S-067</button>.</p>","children":["D5.d1.m1","D5.d1.m2"]},"D5.d1.m1":{"id":"D5.d1.m1","level":4,"parent":"D5.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","The product line: four form factors, one sensor manifold","The manifold-first design rule (S-501)"],"title":"Mechanism 1.1 — The manifold-first design rule (S-501)","body":"<p>Every Kepler device is architected around a shared sensor-and-compute core — the <strong>Kepler Sensor Module (KSM)</strong> — with form-factor-specific carrier boards and enclosures wrapped around it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-501\">S-501</button>. The KSM carries the inertial, environmental, and acoustic sensors plus an edge-inference NPU; the carrier adds only the connectivity, power, and human-interface elements a given context actually needs <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-068\">S-068</button>. This is the exact inverse of the consumer playbook, where each product is designed bespoke to hit a price point and every generation re-validates its own sensor stack from scratch. Kepler deliberately accepts a slightly higher per-unit cost in exchange for a single validated sensor stack that produces <strong>dimensionally consistent data across every context</strong> — a road-vibration reading taken from a vehicle mount and one taken from a courier's handlebar are directly comparable, because they come from the same silicon and the same calibration <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-068\">S-068</button>. That comparability is the entire point of the design rule: it is what makes breadth (B) additive rather than fragmented, and it is the single hardware decision that most directly serves the D6 data platform, which can only fuse the six domains' signals if they arrive pre-aligned.</p><p>The manifold expresses itself in four form factors, one per high-signal surface:</p><ul><li>The <strong>Kepler Beacon (KB-1)</strong> is the flagship consumer-facing device — a palm-sized navigation-and-payments companion that rides on a vehicle dash or a courier's bar, detailed in the mockup below <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-068\">S-068</button>.</li><li>The <strong>Kepler Node (KN-2)</strong> is an embedded industrial module designed to be built directly into D1 vehicles and D2 chargers at the point of manufacture — no enclosure, no screen, pure sensing and telemetry <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-068\">S-068</button>.</li><li>The <strong>Kepler Tag (KT-3)</strong> is a low-cost adhesive asset-tracker for D3 logistics parcels and courier kit, harvesting shock, tilt, and temperature across the delivery graph <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-068\">S-068</button>.</li><li>The <strong>Kepler Counter (KC-4)</strong> is a merchant-facing payment-and-sensing terminal that anchors D4 at the physical point of sale <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-068\">S-068</button>.</li></ul><p>Read together, the four are not a product catalogue but four apertures onto the same manifold — each dropping the identical KSM into a different physical context so that the data lands pre-aligned for D6 rather than needing to be reconciled after the fact.</p>","children":[]},"D5.d1.m2":{"id":"D5.d1.m2","level":4,"parent":"D5.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","The product line: four form factors, one sensor manifold","The product mockup: what the Beacon actually shows (S-502)"],"title":"Mechanism 1.2 — The product mockup: what the Beacon actually shows (S-502)","body":"<p>The KB-1's value to the user has to be real, or the device never gets placed and the sensor never samples <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-069\">S-069</button>. The interface is therefore designed as a genuinely useful navigation-and-payments surface whose data-harvesting is invisible <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-502\">S-502</button>. Every element on the rendered screen is a <strong>cross-domain coupling made visible to the user</strong>: the turn card is D1's routing model rendered locally; the \"4 min to charge\" prompt and the live bay price are D2 telemetry; \"TAP TO PAY $12.40\" is the D4 wallet executing a transaction on the device's secure element; and the air-quality and road-surface read-outs are the D5 manifold showing the user a sliver of what it is measuring — enough to feel useful, nowhere near the full sample <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-069\">S-069</button>.</p><p>The governing design principle follows directly <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-503\">S-503</button>: give the user one visible reason to keep the device powered and mounted for every invisible stream being collected behind it. That principle inverts the metric that actually matters for the business. A device in a drawer samples nothing, so <strong>retention of the hardware in position — not units sold — is the true north-star metric for Devices</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-069\">S-069</button>. The screen is the price Kepler pays to keep the manifold in the world, mounted and sampling, which is why every visible feature is a working piece of a different domain rather than decoration.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The product mockup: what the Beacon actually s","lines":"┌──────────────────────────────────┐│  KEPLER BEACON            <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">9</span>:<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">41</span> ▲  │   &lt;- status: GPS lock, LTE, <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">84</span>% batt│                                   ││   ↰  Turn left <span class=\"k\">in</span> <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">200</span> m          │   &lt;- nav card (fed by D1 routing model)│      onto Orchard Rd              ││   ▓▓▓▓▓▓▓░░░  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">4</span> min to charge     │   &lt;- D2: nearest open bay, live price│                                   ││  ┌─────────────┐  ┌────────────┐ ││  │  TAP TO PAY │  │  AIR: Good │ │   &lt;- D4 on-device wallet | D5 PM2.<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">5</span>│  │   $<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">12.40</span>    │  │  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">22</span> µg/m³  │ ││  └─────────────┘  └────────────┘ ││                                   ││  Road: smooth   ·   Grip: firm    │   &lt;- surfaced sensor read-outs└──────────────────────────────────┘"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D5.d2":{"id":"D5.d2","level":3,"parent":"D5","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","BOM, cost & margin: financing a sensor network with hardware margin"],"title":"Driver 2 — BOM, cost & margin: financing a sensor network with hardware margin","body":"<p>The product line decides what Kepler places and where; the cost structure decides whether that placement is affordable at fleet scale <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-070\">S-070</button>. Devices runs on a deliberately unusual margin philosophy — one that inverts the purpose hardware profit normally serves. Here <strong>hardware margin exists to subsidise sensor coverage, not to maximise device profit</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-070\">S-070</button>. Every KB-1 is priced not to earn on the device but to bankroll the data stream it will emit over its life, and that inversion is what reframes both the bill of materials and the margin waterfall the mechanisms below dissect.</p>","children":["D5.d2.m1","D5.d2.m2"]},"D5.d2.m1":{"id":"D5.d2.m1","level":4,"parent":"D5.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","BOM, cost & margin: financing a sensor network with hardware margin","The BOM cost table and the teardown that names the sensors (S-504, S-505)"],"title":"Mechanism 2.1 — The BOM cost table and the teardown that names the sensors (S-504, S-505)","body":"<p>The KB-1 Beacon's bill of materials is where the strategy stops being a philosophy and becomes concrete <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-071\">S-071</button>. The costed BOM (S-504), struck at a 2m-unit annual run-rate, gives a landed cost per unit — the figure that decides whether fleet-scale placement is affordable at all, and the thing the driver's cost structure is really about <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-071\">S-071</button>.</p><p>The teardown and exploded view (S-505) then name where each of those components physically sits, because <strong>the placement of a sensor determines the quality of the sample it takes</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-071\">S-071</button>. Two placement decisions carry more strategic weight than the BOM table alone can show (S-506).</p><ul><li>The environmental intake vent is engineered to sit above the compute stack, thermally isolated, so the SEN-55 reads true ambient particulate rather than the device's own heat plume — a $0.40 tooling cost that protects the fidelity of a data stream worth far more than the device itself <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-071\">S-071</button>.</li><li>The IMU is bonded rigidly to the mount interface, so vibration couples through the chassis of the D1 vehicle or the D3 handlebar it rides on, turning the whole vehicle into an extension of the sensor <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-071\">S-071</button>.</li></ul><p>These are the design choices that separate a sensor that samples from one that merely reports <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-071\">S-071</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The BOM cost table and the teardown that names","lines":"        KB-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1</span> BEACON — EXPLODED (top to bottom)   ┌───────────────────────────────┐   │  Transflective LCD + touch    │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">8</span>)   ├───────────────────────────────┤   │  Gasket / light pipe          │   ├───────────────────────────────┤   │  Env. intake vent → SEN-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">55</span>    │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span>)  particulate/VOC   │  Knowles MEMS mic array  ○ ○   │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">5</span>)  acoustic fault ID   ├───────────────────────────────┤   │  Main PCB:                     │   │    KSM SoC (NPU)   [▓]         │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1</span>)   │    BMI360 IMU      [·]         │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">2</span>)  vibration/grip   │    ZED-F9 GNSS     [·]         │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">4</span>)   │    SE051 secure el.[·]         │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">6</span>)   │    Quectel modem   [▒]         │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">7</span>)   ├───────────────────────────────┤   │  2000mAh Li-po cell            │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">9</span>)   ├───────────────────────────────┤   │  Housing + connectors         │  (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">10</span>)   └───────────────────────────────┘"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D5.d2.m2":{"id":"D5.d2.m2","level":4,"parent":"D5.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","BOM, cost & margin: financing a sensor network with hardware margin","The margin waterfall: ASP to gross margin, and why it is thin on purpose (S-507)"],"title":"Mechanism 2.2 — The margin waterfall: ASP to gross margin, and why it is thin on purpose (S-507)","body":"<p>The margin waterfall from average selling price to gross margin (S-507), taken per KB-1 unit, lands at a 31% hardware gross margin <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-072\">S-072</button>. Read on its own terms, that number is unremarkable for consumer electronics and would be a disappointment for any other Kepler domain — held against the standalone frame, Devices looks like the portfolio's laggard <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-072\">S-072</button>.</p><p>But <strong>the waterfall is measuring the wrong thing</strong> (S-508). The strategically correct denominator is not device profit; it is the fully-loaded cost of the proprietary data the device generates over its service life <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-072\">S-072</button>. A KB-1 held in position for its ~30-month life emits on the order of tens of millions of sensor-seconds across five independent modalities <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-072\">S-072</button>. Financing that acquisition through a standalone sensor-network build would sit at full expense on D6's cost line — which today runs at −$420m as a cost centre <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-072\">S-072</button>. Instead, the hardware margin pre-pays it: the device sells at a positive gross margin, and the data arrives effectively free to D6 <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-072\">S-072</button>.</p><p>The correct read of the waterfall is therefore not \"31% margin\" but <strong>a proprietary sensor network delivered at negative net acquisition cost</strong> — the number the board should track, and the bridge into Driver 4 <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-072\">S-072</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"waterfall","data":{"unit":"% of ASP","steps":[{"label":"ASP (average selling price)","value":100},{"label":"Less landed cost of goods (BOM + assembly)","value":31},{"label":"Gross margin","value":31}]},"evidence_class":"illustrate"},"children":[]},"D5.d3":{"id":"D5.d3","level":3,"parent":"D5","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","The supply chain: geography as a sensor-coverage decision"],"title":"Driver 3 — The supply chain: geography as a sensor-coverage decision","body":"<p>A sensor network is only as broad as the units Kepler can actually manufacture, land, and place. In <strong>Devices</strong>, the supply chain is therefore not a back-office function — it is the <strong>throttle on how fast breadth (B) compounds</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-073\">S-073</button>, and it is managed as such rather than as a logistics cost line. Every fab constraint, assembly bottleneck, and port chokepoint reads directly as a ceiling on how quickly the sensor mesh — the term that feeds the moat's breadth factor across the 42 cities — can actually widen.</p>","children":["D5.d3.m1","D5.d3.m2"]},"D5.d3.m1":{"id":"D5.d3.m1","level":4,"parent":"D5.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","The supply chain: geography as a sensor-coverage decision","The supply-chain map: fabs, assembly, ports (S-509)"],"title":"Mechanism 3.1 — The supply-chain map: fabs, assembly, ports (S-509)","body":"<p>The physical flow runs from silicon to placement <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-509\">S-509</button>, and two structural choices along it are load-bearing <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-510\">S-510</button>. First, <strong>final assembly is concentrated at Jabil Penang</strong>, with ASE Kaohsiung handling SoC packaging and test — deliberately dual-region against the fab base but single-node on final assembly, trading resilience for the tighter process control that a consistent sensor calibration demands. A sensor that reads differently unit-to-unit corrupts the data term (D) it is supposed to feed, so calibration discipline is allowed to outrank redundancy at this leg.</p><p>Second, the <strong>placement leg is Kepler's own</strong>. Units land at the PSA Singapore and Rotterdam hubs and then ride the D1 mobility fleet and D3 courier network into the field, rather than moving through third-party retail <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-509\">S-509</button>. This is the <strong>distribution coupling that a standalone device maker cannot replicate</strong> — Kepler already has vehicles and couriers moving through all 42 cities daily, so the last mile of device placement is nearly free and rides infrastructure that already exists <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-510\">S-510</button>. Distribution, for a normal hardware company the most expensive way to buy breadth, is here a fixed asset already paid for by two other domains.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The supply-chain map: fabs, assembly, ports (S","lines":"   FABS / SENSOR SOURCES            ASSEMBLY            PORTS → PLACEMENT   ─────────────────────           ──────────          ─────────────────   TSMC Hsinchu (SoC) ──┐   Bosch Reutlingen ────┤   Sensirion Stäfa ─────┼──► ASE Kaohsiung ──► Jabil ──► Port of   u-blox Thalwil ──────┤      (SoC pkg/test)   Penang    Singapore ──► <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14</span>-country   NXP Nijmegen ────────┤                       (final    (PSA hub)     placement   Knowles Itasca ──────┤                        assembly)              via D1/D3   Quectel Shanghai ────┘                          │                    fleet channel                                                    ▼                                            Port of Klang (MY)                                                    │                                         ┌──────────┴──────────┐                                    Rotterdam (EU hub)     Singapore (APAC hub)                                    → Amsterdam DC          → <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">42</span>-city network"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D5.d3.m2":{"id":"D5.d3.m2","level":4,"parent":"D5.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","The supply chain: geography as a sensor-coverage decision","The manufacturing Gantt and the concentration risk it exposes (S-511, S-512)"],"title":"Mechanism 3.2 — The manufacturing Gantt and the concentration risk it exposes (S-511, S-512)","body":"<p>The ramp plots the KB-1 v2 and the embedded KN-2 across quarters from FY26 to FY27 <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-511\">S-511</button>, and the schedule makes one dependency unmissable <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-512\">S-512</button>: <strong>the KN-2 embedded module's mass production is gated on the D1 vehicle manufacturing line</strong>, because the Node is built into vehicles at their point of assembly, not retrofitted afterward. This is the cross-domain coupling expressed as a schedule constraint — Devices cannot ramp its highest-breadth embedded sensor any faster than Mobility ramps the vehicles it lives inside.</p><p>The strategic reading is that <strong>Devices' breadth-compounding is paced by D1's fleet growth</strong>, which is precisely why sequencing — the governing thought — matters: place the sensor line and the vehicle line out of sync and the moat forms slower than the model requires <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-512\">S-512</button>. Get them in phase and every vehicle rolling off D1's line ships a sensor into the field at zero incremental placement cost.</p><p>The Gantt surfaces a second edge case as well — the <strong>concentration risk on Jabil Penang and the single Singapore port hub</strong>. A typhoon-season disruption at Klang or Penang is a direct hit to breadth, not merely to margin, so the FY27 plan carries a <strong>qualified second final-assembly node as insurance</strong>, accepted as a margin cost paid explicitly against sensor-coverage continuity <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-512\">S-512</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The manufacturing Gantt and the concentration ","lines":"                    Q1<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"s\">\"s\"</span>>'<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">26</span>  Q2'</span><span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">26</span>  Q3<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"s\">\"s\"</span>>'<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">26</span>  Q4'</span><span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">26</span>  Q1<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"s\">\"s\"</span>>'<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">27</span>  Q2'</span><span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">27</span> SoC tape-out/qual  ████░░ Sensor sourcing    ░████░ EVT (eng. valid.)   ░███░░ DVT (design valid.)     ░████░ PVT (prod. valid.)        ░███░ Jabil line bring-up        ░████░ Mass prod. KB-1v2             ░██████████████ KN-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">2</span> embed (into D1)              ░████████████   ← gated on D1 vehicle line Cert (CE/FCC/PSA)          ░████░"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D5.d4":{"id":"D5.d4","level":3,"parent":"D5","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","Proprietary sensor data is the real product"],"title":"Driver 4 — Proprietary sensor data is the real product","body":"<p>Everything above in Devices — the four form factors, the thin-on-purpose margin, the fleet-ridden supply chain — exists to serve one end: proprietary sensor data. Devices' claim on the moat is <strong>breadth (B)</strong>, the one term this domain owns, and this driver is where breadth stops being a slogan and becomes measurable value — value that lowers cost and raises trust across the other five domains' P&amp;Ls rather than showing up in a device margin of its own <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-076\">S-076</button>.</p>","children":["D5.d4.m1","D5.d4.m2"]},"D5.d4.m1":{"id":"D5.d4.m1","level":4,"parent":"D5.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","Proprietary sensor data is the real product","The five-modality manifold and its uniqueness (S-513)"],"title":"Mechanism 4.1 — The five-modality manifold and its uniqueness (S-513)","body":"<p>The Kepler manifold captures <strong>five broad, mutually-reinforcing modalities</strong> that no competitor has jointly instrumented at fleet scale <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-513\">S-513</button>:</p><ul><li>kinematic — a 400 Hz 6-axis IMU reading road roughness, grip torque, and crash signatures;</li><li>environmental — particulate, VOC, and humidity sensing that builds air-quality maps street-by-street;</li><li>acoustic — a MEMS array capturing failing-relay and bearing signatures for predictive maintenance;</li><li>positional — dual-band GNSS resolving position to sub-metre, lane-level rather than road-level;</li><li>electrical — battery-cell impedance and charger telemetry carried by the KN-2.</li></ul><p>The uniqueness is <strong>not any single stream</strong> — competitors buy IMUs and GNSS too, and can match Kepler on any one axis. It is the <strong>joint distribution</strong>: only Kepler observes all five from the same calibrated node, time-aligned, across the same 42-city fleet <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-077\">S-077</button>. That co-observation is the raw material breadth is made of, and it is why the sample cannot be reconstructed after the fact by anyone lacking the placed hardware — the modalities correlate node-by-node, and the correlations are the asset, not the streams.</p>","children":[]},"D5.d4.m2":{"id":"D5.d4.m2","level":4,"parent":"D5.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Devices & Hardware","Proprietary sensor data is the real product","How breadth sharpens D6, and the value attribution (S-514, S-515)"],"title":"Mechanism 4.2 — How breadth sharpens D6, and the value attribution (S-514, S-515)","body":"<p>The manifold's payoff is realised in D6's models, and the couplings are specific <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-514\">S-514</button>. <strong>Kinematic</strong> road-roughness data sharpens D1's routing and ride-comfort models and feeds D2's siting — rough corridors correlate with battery-drain hotspots worth a charger. <strong>Acoustic</strong> fault signatures drive predictive maintenance across the D1 fleet and the D2 charger network, converting reactive downtime into scheduled service. <strong>Electrical</strong> telemetry from the KN-2 feeds D2's battery-health and dispatch pricing. And the on-device secure element plus placement context feed D4's fraud model — a payment tap whose device reports an impossible kinematic trajectory is a fraud signal no card network can see.</p><p>The second data table quantifies the attributed lift — Kepler's internal model-improvement attribution from the sensor manifold, FY26 estimate <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-515\">S-515</button>. That table is the answer to the board's fair challenge — <strong>is the compounding real or a story?</strong> Each row is a coupling the governing thought predicts, now carrying a number. Breadth (B) is not an abstraction; it is a <strong>−18% downtime</strong> figure and an <strong>−11% fraud false-positive</strong> figure that land on other domains' P&amp;Ls, not on Devices' own <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-516\">S-516</button>.</p><p>The edge-case worth naming: the environmental modality produces a saleable data product — street-level air quality sold to municipalities — the one place Devices' data monetises directly rather than only through internal model lift. It is a hedge that gives the breadth thesis an external price signal to validate against, so the −18% and −11% attributions are not the only evidence the compounding is real.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["Modality","Primary model fed (domain)","Attributed improvement","Value mechanism"],"rows":[["Kinematic (IMU)","Routing / comfort (D1)","+6.1% route-quality score","Fewer reroutes, higher rider retention (D)"],["Environmental","Air-quality maps (D6→D1)","New data product","Sold to cities; sharpens siting (D2)"],["Acoustic","Predictive maint. (D1/D2)","−18% unplanned downtime","Uptime → trust (T)"],["Electrical","Battery health / dispatch (D2)","+4.3% charge-throughput","Lower marginal cost of energy"],["Positional","Fraud geo-signals (D4)","−11% false-positive fraud","Fewer declined good txns (T)"]],"negCols":[2]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6":{"id":"D6","level":2,"parent":"GT","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform"],"title":"Domain 6 — Data & AI Platform: the moat is not a business, it is the hub of the flywheel","body":"<p>Every other domain section in this document ends by naming which of the four moat terms it moves and which domains it feeds. Domain 6 is where those threads are tied. It is the only domain that does not own a customer, a vehicle, a charger, a courier, or a card — and it is the only domain whose output is the moat identity itself. Read as a P&amp;L it is an embarrassment: a −$420m cost centre, the single largest line item the conglomerate-discount bears say proves Kepler is undisciplined. Read as the spine, it is the reason the other five stop being five. Domain 6 owns and compounds data breadth (B) directly — it is the layer that turns proprietary sensor and behaviour exhaust into features no competitor can assemble — and it is the only layer that touches all four terms of</p><p>because it is the multiplication. D1 produces density, D3 produces liquidity, D2 and D4 produce trust, D5 produces breadth — but M is a product, not a sum, and a product only exists once the terms are computed together on shared features. That computation is Domain 6. The cross-feeds are unusually literal here: Domain 6 ingests D1 location traces, D5 sensor telemetry, D3 marketplace supply–demand events, and D4 fraud/settlement signals, and it serves models back — routing, siting, matching, scoring, safety — that raise D1's density, D2's reliability, D3's liquidity, and D4's approval rates. The flywheel is not a metaphor Domain 6 illustrates; it is the graph Domain 6 runs. This section opens the hub, walks its four drivers, and closes on what is settled versus what the next decade is decided by.</p>","finding":"One decision that determines the decade is whether the…","finding_full":"<p>What's settled. The six businesses are real and at scale; the conglomerate discount is real; the moat identity's four terms are each measurable; and the cross-feeds are technically demonstrable domain by domain. None of that is in dispute.</p><p>What counts. The one decision that determines the decade is whether the board funds Kepler as a flywheel — hub first, sequenced, cross-feeds instrumented and made legible — or as six businesses to be optimised or spun apart. The first multiplies four terms into an uncatchable moat and inverts the discount; the second severs the wiring and confirms the medio</p>","children":["D6.d1","D6.d2","D6.d3","D6.d4"]},"D6.d1":{"id":"D6.d1","level":3,"parent":"D6","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The platform architecture: one ingestion spine, one feature store, one serving layer"],"title":"Driver 1 — The platform architecture: one ingestion spine, one feature store, one serving layer","body":"<p>The first driver is the least glamorous and the most decisive: there is exactly <strong>one data platform, not six</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-081\">S-081</button>. This is not a preference for tidiness; it is the load-bearing precondition for everything the Data &amp; AI Platform claims to do, because the moat identity M = D × B × L × T multiplies its terms rather than adding them, and a term cannot be multiplied by a domain that cannot read it.</p><p>The conglomerate failure mode is not strategic disagreement — it is six teams each standing up their own warehouse, their own feature definitions, their own model registry, so that \"rider dwell time\" means one thing in D1 and a subtly different thing in D3, and the join that would have produced a feature never happens <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-081\">S-081</button>. Divergence of that kind is silent: nobody decides to fragment the data, it fragments by default the moment six schemas are allowed to drift. Domain 6's architecture exists to make that divergence structurally impossible — one ingestion spine, one feature store, one serving layer, built so the pipes come before anything that flows through them.</p>","children":["D6.d1.m1","D6.d1.m2","D6.d1.m3"]},"D6.d1.m1":{"id":"D6.d1.m1","level":4,"parent":"D6.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The platform architecture: one ingestion spine, one feature store, one serving layer","A single ingestion spine that normalises six event streams into one grammar"],"title":"Mechanism 1.1 — A single ingestion spine that normalises six event streams into one grammar","body":"<p>Every physical-world interaction across the estate emits an event: a ride start, a charge session, a courier accept, a card authorisation, a device heartbeat <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-082\">S-082</button>. All six domains publish to a <strong>single append-only event bus</strong> — Kepler calls it the Interaction Log — under one canonical schema: entity_id, geohash, t, domain, event_type, payload, trust_context <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-601\">S-601</button>. The schema is the whole trick. Because every domain speaks the same seven-field grammar, an event from D2 charging and an event from D4 payments land in the same log, keyed the same way, and become joinable without a translation layer that would never have been built. At 28.4m MAU across 42 cities, the spine ingests ~3.9bn events/day at peak <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-082\">S-082</button> — a volume that only stays coherent because there is one grammar rather than six.</p><p>The point of one grammar is the <strong>point-in-time join</strong>: any feature can be reconstructed as it was known at decision time, so a fraud model never trains on settlement data that only existed after the authorisation <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-602\">S-602</button>. That guardrail against label leakage is not a modelling nicety — it is what makes cross-domain signal safe to use at all. It is what lets D4 signals safely sharpen D1–D3 without leakage, a cross-feed that is impossible in a six-warehouse world because the timestamps never reconcile <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-602\">S-602</button>. The architecture diagram is the physical shape of the platform, and every later mechanism is a path through it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-601\">S-601</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"A single ingestion spine that normalises six e","lines":"                         KEPLER DATA &amp; AI PLATFORM — SYSTEM ARCHITECTURE                         (ingestion → feature store → models → serving)  SOURCES                INGESTION            FEATURE STORE          MODELS            SERVING ┌────────┐   events   ┌───────────┐  clean  ┌──────────────┐  vec  ┌─────────┐  API ┌──────────┐ │ D1 ride│──────────▶ │           │────────▶│ offline (parq)│─────▶ │ routing │────▶ │ D1 fleet │ │ D2 chg │──────────▶ │ Interaction│         │  + online (kv)│      │ siting  │      │ D2 dispat│ │ D3 mkt │──────────▶ │   Log bus │  dedup  │              │  ⟳    │ matching│      │ D3 match │ │ D4 pay │──────────▶ │  (Kafka)  │────────▶│  point-<span class=\"k\">in</span>-   │◀─────│ scoring │────▶ │ D4 auth  │ │ D5 dev │──────────▶ │  + Flink  │  PII    │  time joins  │ label │ safety  │      │ D5 OTA   │ │ ext geo│──────────▶ │  normalise│  vault  │              │      │ demand  │      │ dashbds  │ └────────┘            └───────────┘         └──────────────┘      └─────────┘      └──────────┘                            │                       ▲   │              ▲                 │                       trust_context           feature  └── training ──┘         model outputs                       tagging (D4) ───────────▶ registry      registry ◀── eval/ROC (Driver <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">3</span>)                                                (S-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">603</span>)         (S-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">611</span>)          feedback ⟳ (Driver <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">4</span>)"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6.d1.m2":{"id":"D6.d1.m2","level":4,"parent":"D6.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The platform architecture: one ingestion spine, one feature store, one serving layer","A feature store that is the physical form of data breadth (B)"],"title":"Mechanism 1.2 — A feature store that is the physical form of data breadth (B)","body":"<p>The Interaction Log is raw; the feature store is where <strong>breadth B actually lives</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-083\">S-083</button>. Raw events are not features — breadth is not the count of streams, it is the count of computed, reusable signals every domain can draw on. The feature store holds two mirrored surfaces: an offline store (columnar, for training) and an online store (key-value, sub-10ms, for serving), guaranteeing train/serve parity so a model sees the same value in production that it saw in training <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-603\">S-603</button>. A feature computed once — say geohash_demand_z_15m, the 15-minute demand z-score for a location — is available to D1 routing, D2 siting, and D3 matching from the same row <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-603\">S-603</button>.</p><p>This is the precise mechanism by which B compounds instead of fragmenting: each new domain does not add a warehouse, it adds columns other domains can read <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-083\">S-083</button>. In a six-warehouse world that same z-score is computed three times, three subtly different ways, and shared by none; here it is one row read by three consumers, and the marginal domain lifts the breadth term for all of them.</p><p>Note feat_entity.trust_score and feat_entity.pay_default_pd: those columns are written by D4 and read by D1 — to decide which riders can go cash-free — the payments-closes-the-loop coupling made concrete as two columns in one table <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-083\">S-083</button>. The cross-feed the flywheel depends on is not an integration project; it is a column reference.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["Feature-store table","Grain","Key columns","Refresh","Primary consumers"],"rows":[["feat_location","geohash-7 × 15min","demand_z, dwell_p50, charge_gap_min, incident_rate_90d","streaming","D1, D2, D3"],["feat_entity","user/device × day","trust_score, mob_freq_30d, pay_default_pd, sensor_health","hourly","D4, D5, D1"],["feat_edge","origin→dest × hour","eta_resid, match_prob, courier_supply_z, surge_state","streaming","D3, D1"],["feat_asset","vehicle/charger × 5min","soc_pct, util_rate, fault_flag, telemetry_drift","streaming","D2, D5, D1"]],"negCols":[]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6.d1.m3":{"id":"D6.d1.m3","level":4,"parent":"D6.d1","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The platform architecture: one ingestion spine, one feature store, one serving layer","A serving layer that returns models to the domains that fed them"],"title":"Mechanism 1.3 — A serving layer that returns models to the domains that fed them","body":"<p>Breadth is inert until it is served back — a feature store no domain can query at decision time is just an expensive archive. The serving layer exposes every model behind <strong>one low-latency API with a shared contract</strong>, so a domain requests a decision — route, site, match, authorise, flag — and receives it in &lt;60ms p95 without knowing which features or which upstream domains produced it <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-604\">S-604</button>. The abstraction is the point: a consumer domain does not integrate against five other domains, it integrates against one contract, and the hub resolves the rest. This is the architectural expression of \"all five draw from the hub\" <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-604\">S-604</button>.</p><p>It also means a model improvement — better ETA residuals from richer D5 telemetry, say — propagates to every consumer at once, rather than being re-implemented five times <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-604\">S-604</button>. One improvement, served through one API, lifts every domain that reads it simultaneously; that is compounding rather than copying. Driver 1 has now built the pipes — one spine, one feature store, one serving layer; Driver 2 explains what flows through them and why it compounds <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-084\">S-084</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D6.d2":{"id":"D6.d2","level":3,"parent":"D6","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The data flywheel: how five domains' data compounds into one moat"],"title":"Driver 2 — The data flywheel: how five domains' data compounds into one moat","body":"<p>The architecture is necessary but not sufficient. A pipe that carries six streams to six destinations is still a conglomerate with good plumbing — real infrastructure, no moat. The flywheel is the sharper claim: each domain's data raises the value of every other domain's data <strong>super-additively</strong>, so breadth B is not the sum of six datasets but their product on shared keys <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-085\">S-085</button>. Driver 2 is the mechanism of that compounding, and its centrepiece is the data-flow Sankey and the flywheel network graph — the two pictures that show the multiplication rather than the addition, and the place where the moat identity M = D × B × L × T either earns its multiplication sign or does not.</p>","children":["D6.d2.m1","D6.d2.m2","D6.d2.m3"]},"D6.d2.m1":{"id":"D6.d2.m1","level":4,"parent":"D6.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The data flywheel: how five domains' data compounds into one moat","Cross-domain joins create features no single domain could hold"],"title":"Mechanism 2.1 — Cross-domain joins create features no single domain could hold","body":"<p>The compounding is concrete, and it lives in specific joins no single-vertical firm can compute. <strong>S-605</strong>: D1 location traces, D5 accelerometer telemetry, and D3 courier GPS join on geohash × t to produce two features — `road_roughness` and `curb_availability`. Neither is a curiosity. Road_roughness improves D1 routing and D3 drop-off ETA at the same time, and curb_availability feeds D2 charger-siting, because rough approach roads depress charger utilisation <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-086\">S-086</button>. No competitor with only a rideshare app, or only a delivery app, can compute either feature — none holds all three streams on one key, so the join simply does not exist inside their data.</p><p><strong>S-606</strong> is the second join, and it points at trust rather than routing. D4 authorisation outcomes join to D1 rider history and D5 device fingerprint to lift the fraud model. A card-decline pattern that reads as noise in isolation becomes explicable once the same entity's mobility regularity and device health are columns in the same row — a legitimate rider on a healthy device is a different risk than the identical decline attached to neither <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-086\">S-086</button>.</p><p>The data-flow Sankey makes the accumulation visible: the six sources are the left band, the moat is the single right node, and each ribbon's width is the share of the moat's feature value that source contributes. That last line is the whole argument in one number. The <strong>+19% cross-join uplift</strong> is feature value that literally cannot exist for a focused specialist, because producing it requires two streams the specialist does not both own <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-086\">S-086</button>. It is the quantified answer to the SCQA's question — the compounding is real, not a story, and it is measurable as the fraction of served feature value that lives only on joins.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Cross-domain joins create features no single d","lines":"        DATA-FLOW SANKEY — six domains → the moat (ribbon width = feature-value contribution)  D1 Mobility      ████████████████████████████  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">34</span>%  ┐  D5 Devices       ██████████████████            <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">22</span>%  ┤  D3 Logistics     ████████████                  <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">16</span>%  ┤        ┌───────────────┐  D4 Payments      ██████████                    <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">13</span>%  ┼──────▶ │  THE MOAT (M) │  D2 Energy        ████████                       <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">9</span>%  ┤        │  B compounded │  ext / partner    ██████                         <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">6</span>%  ┘        └───────────────┘                                                 ───                                                 <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">100</span>%   Cross-join uplift (features that exist ONLY on ≥<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">2</span> joined streams): +<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">19</span>% of served feature value   → this band is the flywheel: it is zero <span class=\"k\">for</span> any standalone competitor."},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6.d2.m2":{"id":"D6.d2.m2","level":4,"parent":"D6.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The data flywheel: how five domains' data compounds into one moat","The flywheel network graph: the coherency centrepiece"],"title":"Mechanism 2.2 — The flywheel network graph: the coherency centrepiece","body":"<p>If the Sankey shows how much each domain feeds the moat, the network graph shows that every feed is also a return — the loop that makes the wheel a wheel. This is the single most important picture in the section: the six domains as nodes, the moat as the hub, and directed edges running in both directions — raw data in, models out <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-087\">S-087</button>.</p><p><strong>S-607</strong>: the graph is directed, and the strategic content lives in the return edges, not the input ones.</p><ul><li>D1 sends traces and receives routing and safety models that raise density D by cutting deadhead miles <strong>~11%</strong>.</li><li>D4 sends fraud and settlement signals and receives a credit model that raises trust T — which is precisely what lets D1 and D3 run cash-free.</li><li>D5 sends proprietary sensor telemetry — the breadth B no competitor holds — and receives OTA and health models back.</li></ul><p>Delete the hub and the picture collapses into six unconnected nodes. That collapse is the visual proof of the governing thought: the conglomerate discount is the market pricing the six nodes on a sum-of-the-parts basis; the flywheel is the edges the market cannot see, because a return edge never shows up in any single domain's standalone P&amp;L <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-087\">S-087</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"The flywheel network graph: the coherency cent","lines":"              FLYWHEEL NETWORK GRAPH — six domains feeding &amp; fed by the moat (D6 hub)                                   ┌─────────────┐                    location ─────▶│   D1        │◀───── routing, safety models                    behaviour      │  MOBILITY   │       (raises density D)                                   └─────┬───────┘                        electrons ▲      │ traces         ▲ siting model (raises T)                   ┌─────────────┐│      ▼                │┌─────────────┐        util model │   D2        ││  ┌───────────┐        ││   D5        │       ───────────▶│  ENERGY     │└─▶│           │◀───────┘│  DEVICES    │◀── OTA/health model                   └─────────────┘   │  D6  MOAT │  sensor └─────────────┘   (raises B)                        supply▲      │  (hub, M) │  telem       ▲                   ┌─────────────┐   │           │        ┌─────────────┐      match model  │   D3        │──▶│           │◀───────│   D4        │  fraud/credit model       ───────────▶│ LOGISTICS   │   └───────────┘  auth  │  PAYMENTS   │──▶ (raises trust T)                   └─────────────┘     ▲   fraud+trust     └─────────────┘                                       │   signals close the loop (T)     Every edge <span class=\"k\">IN</span> (data) has a paired edge OUT (model). Remove D6 and the graph is six isolated nodes."},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6.d2.m3":{"id":"D6.d2.m3","level":4,"parent":"D6.d2","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The data flywheel: how five domains' data compounds into one moat","Compounding shows up as a rising blended contribution"],"title":"Mechanism 2.3 — Compounding shows up as a rising blended contribution","body":"<p>The flywheel's output is economic, and the number is the one the entire document is anchored to: blended contribution per interaction rising from <strong>−0.31</strong> over ten years. Mechanism 2.3 attributes that swing to the moat rather than to any one domain's margin <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-088\">S-088</button>.</p><p><strong>S-608</strong>: each 10% rise in served feature value — mostly the cross-join band from Mechanism 2.1 — lowers three marginal costs at once: the cost of a mobility decision (fewer empty miles), of a logistics match (higher fill), and of a payment authorisation (fewer false declines). They fall together because all three read the same improved features <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-088\">S-088</button>. That simultaneity is the point. One investment in breadth pays out across four domains at once, which is why Domain 6's <strong>−$420m</strong> is not a cost centre but the price of the multiplier — the line item that buys the multiplication sign in M = D × B × L × T. Driver 3 is how that feature value becomes decisions <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-088\">S-088</button>.</p>","children":[]},"D6.d3":{"id":"D6.d3","level":3,"parent":"D6","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The models: turning compounded breadth into decisions that move D, L, and T"],"title":"Driver 3 — The models: turning compounded breadth into decisions that move D, L, and T","body":"<p>Features are potential; models are where the moat is realised. Driver 3 is the conversion layer — the point at which breadth <strong>B</strong> is turned into the three terms that actually move the number: density <strong>D</strong> through routing, liquidity <strong>L</strong> through matching, and trust <strong>T</strong> through scoring and safety <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-089\">S-089</button>. The strategic claim underneath is blunt: the models are better because the data is broader. A claim like that is only worth stating if it is shown rather than asserted, which is why this driver carries model-performance evidence — ROC curves and a confusion matrix with real figures — instead of a narrative about model quality <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-089\">S-089</button>. The curve below is that evidence: the same fraud/trust model scored on D4 data alone against the full cross-domain join, with the operating point held at a fixed 0.5% false-positive rate so the gain is read as recall, not as a moved goalpost <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-089\">S-089</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"time-series","data":{"unit":"recall (TPR) vs false-positive rate","series":[{"name":"D4 data only (AUC 0.883)","dash":"4 3","pts":[[0,0],[0.005,0.712],[1,1]]},{"name":"Full cross-domain join (AUC 0.947)","dash":"0","pts":[[0,0],[0.005,0.899],[1,1]]}],"mark":{"name":"0.5% FPR operating point: 71.2% -> 89.9% recall","x":0.005,"y":0.899}},"evidence_class":"illustrate"},"children":["D6.d3.m1","D6.d3.m2","D6.d3.m3"]},"D6.d3.m1":{"id":"D6.d3.m1","level":4,"parent":"D6.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The models: turning compounded breadth into decisions that move D, L, and T","A shared model registry so one improvement propagates to five domains"],"title":"Mechanism 3.1 — A shared model registry so one improvement propagates to five domains","body":"<p>The first mechanism is organisational, not statistical: <strong>models are not owned by domains</strong>. Every model is registered in a single shared registry with tracked lineage and consumed through one serving API, so no domain runs a private copy <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-090\">S-090</button>. The routing model, the matching model, and the fraud model all draw from the same underlying feature tables. That shared substrate is what makes one improvement propagate: lift a single feature — say `feat_location.demand_z`, improved by folding in D2 charge-gap data — and routing, matching, and fraud all inherit the gain at once, because all three read that column <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-090\">S-090</button>. This is the concrete content of *sequence, don't silo*. A siloed org retrains three models three times against three partial datasets and pays the retraining cost three times over, each on a thinner slice of the truth; the platform retrains the feature once and every consuming model inherits it for free <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-090\">S-090</button>. One write, five readers — the propagation is the flywheel doing arithmetic, and it is why a broad platform pulls ahead of three narrow specialists even when none of the three is individually worse.</p>","children":[]},"D6.d3.m2":{"id":"D6.d3.m2","level":4,"parent":"D6.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The models: turning compounded breadth into decisions that move D, L, and T","Model performance demonstrably tracks data breadth"],"title":"Mechanism 3.2 — Model performance demonstrably tracks data breadth","body":"<p>The claim that breadth *causes* performance is not left as rhetoric — Domain 6 tests it by ablation. Each model is trained twice: once on a single-domain feature set, once on the full cross-joined set, and the lift between them is measured directly <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-091\">S-091</button>. The figures here are the fraud/trust model, chosen because it is the cleanest labelled problem and because it is the D4 coupling made visible <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-091\">S-091</button>.</p><p>The result is decisive. AUC moves from <strong>0.883 on D4 data alone to 0.947 on the full cross-domain join</strong>, and at a fixed 0.5% false-positive rate recall rises from 71.2% to 89.9% — an <strong>+18.7-point</strong> improvement <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-610\">S-610</button>. Every point of that lift comes from joining D1 mobility-regularity and D5 device-health features onto the D4 fraud label; nothing about the D4 model itself changed <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-610\">S-610</button>. That delta is the entire flywheel compressed into one confusion matrix: the false decline a single-vertical specialist is forced to eat, Kepler catches — not because its model is cleverer, but because the specialist never holds the mobility and device streams to join in the first place <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-610\">S-610</button>. And higher recall at a fixed false-positive rate is trust <strong>T</strong> stated precisely — fewer fraud losses and fewer false declines at once — served straight back into D4 approval rates, where it lifts the very number the payments domain is judged on <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-610\">S-610</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"Model performance demonstrably tracks data bre","lines":"   ROC — fraud/trust model (S-<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">610</span>)              CONFUSION MATRIX @ operating point (<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.5</span>% FPR)   TPR                                                        PREDICTED   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1.0</span> |            ╭────────── full (AUC <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.947</span>)              │  legit    fraud       |         ╭──╯                                  ┌──────┼─────────────────   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.8</span> |      ╭──╯   ╭──────── D4-only (AUC <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.883</span>)   A │legit │ <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1</span>,<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">984</span>,<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">120</span>   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">9</span>,<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">940</span>   (FPR <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.50</span>%)       |     ╱    ╭──╯                                C │      │   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.6</span> |    ╱  ╭──╯                                   T │fraud │   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1</span>,<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">610</span>   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">14</span>,<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">320</span>   (recall <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">89.9</span>%)       |   ╱ ╭─╯                                      U │      │   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.4</span> |  ╱╭─╯          full model adds D1 mobility   A └──────┴─────────────────       | ╱╭╯            regularity + D5 device health   Precision <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">59.0</span>% · Recall <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">89.9</span>% · at <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.5</span>% FPR   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.2</span> |╱╯              → AUC <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.883</span> → <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.947</span>            Single-domain (D4-only) recall at same FPR: <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">71.2</span>%       |╯                                              Cross-domain uplift: +<span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">18.7</span> pts recall   <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.0</span> +──────────────────────────  FPR                (this delta is the flywheel, <span class=\"k\">in</span> one model)      <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.0</span>        <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">0.5</span>        <span <span class=\"k\">class</span>=\"nu\">1.0</span>"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6.d3.m3":{"id":"D6.d3.m3","level":4,"parent":"D6.d3","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The models: turning compounded breadth into decisions that move D, L, and T","A feature pipeline that any domain can extend but not fork"],"title":"Mechanism 3.3 — A feature pipeline that any domain can extend but not fork","body":"<p>A model is only as trustworthy as the features feeding it, so the feature pipeline is not a convenience script — it is versioned, shared code <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-092\">S-092</button>. A domain adds a feature by contributing a transform into that shared pipeline, which enforces point-in-time correctness and train/serve parity on the way in; what it cannot do is fork a private copy and let it drift <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-092\">S-092</button>. The pipeline shown here computes the cross-domain `road_roughness` feature that three separate domains consume off a single definition <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-605\">S-605</button>. Authored once, read three times — and the quality gate on `sensor_health` is the D5 coupling made executable, refusing bad device telemetry before it can poison a downstream decision <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-092\">S-092</button>. That is the discipline that keeps the registry in Mechanism 3.1 honest: extension is open, forking is closed, so breadth accumulates into one trusted surface instead of fragmenting into private copies that quietly disagree. Driver 3 has turned breadth into decisions; Driver 4 is why those decisions stay defensible across a decade <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-092\">S-092</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"code","data":{"file":"A feature pipeline that any domain can extend ","lines":"<span class=\"c\"># feature: road_roughness  (S-605, S-612) — joins D1 traces + D5 telemetry + D3 courier GPS@feature(store=\"feat_location\", grain=\"geohash7x15min\", pit=True)  # point-in-time enforceddef road_roughness(ctx):    d1 = ctx.stream(\"D1.ride\")   .select(\"geohash7\", \"t\", \"speed_var\")    d5 = ctx.stream(\"D5.device\") .select(\"geohash7\", \"t\", \"accel_rms\", \"sensor_health\")    d3 = ctx.stream(\"D3.courier\").select(\"geohash7\", \"t\", \"gps_jitter\")    j  = pit_join([d1, d5, d3], on=[\"geohash7\", \"t\"], window=\"15min\")   # no leakage    j  = j.filter(col(\"sensor_health\") &gt; 0.8)                           # D5 quality gate    rough = (0.5*z(j.accel_rms) + 0.3*z(j.speed_var) + 0.2*z(j.gps_jitter))    return rough.clip(-4, 4).alias(\"road_roughness\")   # served to D1 routing, D2 siting, D3 ETA</span>"},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6.d4":{"id":"D6.d4","level":3,"parent":"D6","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The moat compounding: the M identity made real, and made uncatchable"],"title":"Driver 4 — The moat compounding: the M identity made real, and made uncatchable","body":"<p>The final driver is the thesis itself, folded back on the machinery that precedes it. Drivers 1 through 3 do work you can point at — they build the pipes, compound the breadth, and serve the models. Driver 4 does something different: it states <strong>why the result is a moat rather than a mere collection of capabilities</strong> — an advantage that widens as Kepler runs rather than eroding — and it discharges that claim by tying every term of the moat identity M = D × B × L × T back to a specific mechanism developed above <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-093\">S-093</button>. Nothing here is new evidence; it is the accounting that shows the earlier evidence multiplies.</p>","children":["D6.d4.m1","D6.d4.m2","D6.d4.m3"]},"D6.d4.m1":{"id":"D6.d4.m1","level":4,"parent":"D6.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The moat compounding: the M identity made real, and made uncatchable","Each term of M is moved by a named mechanism, and D6 multiplies them"],"title":"Mechanism 4.1 — Each term of M is moved by a named mechanism, and D6 multiplies them","body":"<p>M is a product, and Domain 6 is where the multiplication physically happens. The accounting is exact: for each of the four terms, name which mechanism above moves it, which cross-feed carries the lift, and the trajectory it is on <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-094\">S-094</button>. That per-term ledger is the point — the moat is not asserted, it is reconciled line by line to work already shown.</p><p>The consequence is mathematical, not rhetorical. Because M is multiplicative, moving breadth <strong>B by 2.4× while the other three terms rise 1.5–1.9× does not add — it multiplies</strong>, so M compounds far faster than any single term improves <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-613\">S-613</button>. This is the arithmetic core of \"one flywheel, not six\": a conglomerate stacks P&amp;Ls and grows linearly; the flywheel multiplies moat terms and grows super-linearly. And the multiplication is not an accident of branding — Domain 6 is the only layer where the terms meet on shared features and actually compose, rather than sitting in six separate warehouses being added <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-613\">S-613</button>.</p>","component":{"family":"faceted-grid","data":{"cols":["Term","What D6 does to it","Mechanism (trace)","Cross-feed","Today → 10y"],"rows":[["D density","Routing/safety models cut deadhead, raise trips/vehicle-hr","3.1, served via 1.3 (S-609)","serves D1; fed by D1 traces","index 100 → 168"],["B breadth","Feature store + cross-joins; +19% join-only value","1.2, 2.1 (S-603, S-605)","fed by D5 sensors, D1 loc","100 → 240"],["L liquidity","Matching model raises fill rate & courier supply-z","3.1 (S-609)","serves D3; fed by D3 supply","100 → 155"],["T trust","Fraud/credit model: recall 71→90% at fixed FPR","3.2 (S-610)","serves D4; fed by D4 signals","100 → 190"]],"negCols":[]},"evidence_class":"evidence"},"children":[]},"D6.d4.m2":{"id":"D6.d4.m2","level":4,"parent":"D6.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The moat compounding: the M identity made real, and made uncatchable","The moat widens with scale, so sequencing beats focus"],"title":"Mechanism 4.2 — The moat widens with scale, so sequencing beats focus","body":"<p>The moat does not merely persist at scale — it widens, and that single property is what turns sequencing from housekeeping into strategy. The cross-join uplift is a function of how many streams share a key: the <strong>Sankey's +19% and the ROC's +18.7 points grow every time a domain is sequenced onto the platform</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-614\">S-614</button>. This is precisely the asymmetry the bear case cannot see. A focused specialist adding users gets more of the same data along one axis; Kepler adding a domain gets a new dimension that multiplies against every dimension already present. Breadth term B therefore has increasing returns.</p><p>That is the edge case the bears miss. At small scale the conglomerate discount is correct — six mediocre verticals, each trailing a specialist, honestly worth less summed than a break-up would unlock. But increasing returns on B guarantee a crossover: a scale beyond which the flywheel dominates focus and the discount inverts into a premium. <strong>Sequencing is choosing when to cross that line</strong> <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-614\">S-614</button>.</p><p>And the order is not free. Breadth-heavy domains — D5 devices, D1 mobility — must land before the models that monetise them, D4 credit and D3 matching, or the models train on thin data and the compounding stalls before it starts <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-615\">S-615</button>. The platform is the reason the sequence has a right answer at all: only a shared substrate makes \"build breadth first, monetise second\" a physical constraint rather than a preference.</p>","children":[]},"D6.d4.m3":{"id":"D6.d4.m3","level":4,"parent":"D6.d4","path":["Kepler — The Flywheel Decade","Data & AI Platform","The moat compounding: the M identity made real, and made uncatchable","The cost centre is the moat's price, and it is falling per unit of M"],"title":"Mechanism 4.3 — The cost centre is the moat's price, and it is falling per unit of M","body":"<p>The cost centre is not a wound; it is the moat's price tag, and it is falling per unit of M. <strong>Domain 6's −420m is the amortising fixed cost of the multiplier</strong> — the shared substrate that lifts blended contribution per interaction from −0.31 across all six domains at once <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-616\">S-616</button>. The divide between the two readings is entirely accounting posture: the bears expense the hub as a standing loss, while the thesis capitalises it as the asset whose returns show up in every other domain's margin <button class=\"cite\" data-cite=\"S-616\">S-616</button>. As M compounds, the same −420m buys more moat, so the cost per unit of advantage declines even as the headline figure holds.</p>","children":[]}},"roots":["D1","D2","D3","D4","D5","D6"]};
